| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"|  Porter\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Redd\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Reese\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| {{sort|Resetti|[[Mr. Resetti]]}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Rover\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Sable\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Saharah \n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"|  Serena \n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Timmy & Tommy \n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Tom Nook]] \n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Tortimer\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"|  Wendell \n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"|  Wilbur \n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Wisp\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| data-sort-value=\"Y\" {{Yes2|{{Abbr|DLC|Available through the \"Welcome Amiibo\" game update.}}}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Zipper T. Bunny\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| data-sort-value=\"Y\" {{Yes2|{{Abbr|DLC|Available through a free post-release game update.}}}}\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"fourhundred\">{{cite web |last1=Nairn |first1=Lacie |title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons' Recruitable Villagers, Ranked |url=https://www.cbr.com/animal-crossing-new-horizons-recruitable-villagers-ranked/ |website=[[Comic Book Resources]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ACNL\">{{cite web |last1=Heller |first1=Emily |title=Here\u2019s when you can unlock Animal Crossing: New Horizons on Switch |url=https://www.polygon.com/nintendo-switch/2020/3/19/21186825/animal-crossing-new-horizons-release-what-time-play-nintendo-switch-digital-download-e-shop |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ACNLPatch1\">{{cite web |last1=Dell-Cornejo |first1=Daniel |title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons Direct breakdown \u2013 All new and returning features |url=https://nintendowire.com/news/2020/02/20/animal-crossing-new-horizons-direct-breakdown/ |website=Nintendo Wire |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ACNLPatch2\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Julia |title=Animal Crossing: New Horizons\u2019 Bunny Day event detailed, Leif revealed |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/26/21195302/animal-crossing-new-horizons-bunny-day-event-leif |website=Polygon |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.animal-crossing.com/}}\n\n{{Animal Crossing series}}\n\n[[Category:Animal Crossing]]\n[[Category:Lists of video game characters|Animal Crossing]]\n[[Category:Lists of Nintendo characters]]\n", "name_user": "Morgan695", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAppearances by title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characters_in_the_Animal_Crossing_series"}
{"title_page": "Siyum HaShas", "text_new": "{{short description|celebration of the completion of the Daf Yomi}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name              = Siyum HaShas\n|native_name       = {{Nobold|{{Hebrew|\u05e1\u05d9\u05d5\u05dd \u05d4\u05e9\"\u05e1}}}}\n|native_name_lang  = Hebrew\n|logo              = Siyum logo.png\n|logo_alt          = \n|logo_caption      = Logo of the main Siyum HaShas organized by [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n|logo_size         = \n|image             =\n|image_size        = \n|alt               = \n|caption           = Audience view of the 12th Siyum HaShas at [[MetLife Stadium]]\n|status            = Active\n|genre             = \n|date              = \n|frequency         = Every 2,711 days\n|venue             = International\n|location          = \n|coordinates       = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> \n|country           = \n|years_active      = {{age|1923|9|11}} \n|first             = {{start date|df=yes|1931|02|02}}\n|founder_name      = Rabbi [[Meir Shapiro]]\n|last              = \n|prev              = January 1, 2020\n|next              = June 7, 2027\n|participants      = \n|attendance        = 92,000\n|capacity          =\n|area              = \n|budget            = \n|activity          = \n|leader_name       =\n|patron            = \n|organized         = [[World Agudath Israel]]\n|filing            = \n|people            = \n|member            = \n|sponsor           = <!-- | or sponsors = -->\n|current           = \n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Siyum HaShas''' ({{lang-he|\u05e1\u05d9\u05d5\u05dd \u05d4\u05e9\"\u05e1}}, lit. \"completion of the Six Orders [of the Talmud]\") is a celebration of the completion of the [[Daf Yomi]] (daily [[Talmud]] folio) program, a roughly seven-and-a-half-year cycle of learning the Oral [[Torah]] and its commentaries, in which each of the 2,711 pages of the Babylonian Talmud are covered in sequence - one page per day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/siyum-hashas-ad-campaign-commences-ticket-info-to-be-available-after-sukkos |title=Siyum Hashas Ad Campaign Commences, Ticket Info to Be Available After Sukkos |first=Shmiel |last=Gellman |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |publisher=matzav.com}}</ref> The first Daf Yomi cycle began on the first day of [[Rosh Hashanah]] 5684 (11 September 1923); the thirteenth cycle concluded on January 4, 2020 and the fourteenth cycle began the following day, to be concluded on June 7, 2027. The Siyum HaShas marks both the end of the previous cycle and the beginning of the next, and is characterized by inspiring speeches and rousing singing and dancing. The next day they arise in the morning and restart the entire  process, each day, one daf (page).\n\nFor Jews for whom [[Torah study]] is a daily obligation, the publicity and excitement surrounding the Siyum HaShas has resulted in more participants, more Daf Yomi ''[[Shiur (Torah)|shiurim]]'' (lessons), and more Siyum locations with each cycle.<ref name=\"daf7\"/> Since 1990, attendance at the main Siyum HaShas in America, organized by the [[Agudath Israel of America]], has increased dramatically, necessitating the booking of larger arenas and stadiums.<ref name=\"klass\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishpress.com/sections/community/upcoming-events/the-twelfth-siyum-hashas-of-daf-yomi/2012/07/26/ |title=The Twelfth Siyum HaShas Of Daf Yomi|first=Rabbi Yaakov |last=Klass |work=[[The Jewish Press]] |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref> The 13th Siyum HaShas on January 1, 2020 took place in [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[New Jersey]] with a sellout crowd of over 90,000. Other organizations, such as [[Dirshu]], and neighborhood groups and [[synagogues]] in cities around the world, also hold Siyum HaShas events expected to attract tens of thousands of participants.\n\n==Background==\n{{main article|Daf Yomi}}\n[[File:Meir Shapiro.jpg|thumb|upright|Rabbi Meir Shapiro, initiator of Daf Yomi.]]\nThe novel idea of Jews in all parts of the world studying the same ''daf''<ref>A ''daf'', or ''blatt'' in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], consists of both sides of the page.</ref> each day, with the goal of completing the entire Talmud, was put forth at the First World Congress of the [[World Agudath Israel]] in [[Vienna]] on 16 August 1923 by Rabbi [[Meir Shapiro]], then [[Rav]] of [[Sanok]], Poland, and future [[rosh yeshiva]] of the [[Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva]].<ref name=\"daf1\">Shlomi, B. \"A Brilliant Idea: Daf Yomi\". ''[[Hamodia]]'' Magazine, 3 May 2012, pp. 18\u201320.</ref> In those years, only some of the 63 tractates of the Talmud were being studied regularly, such as ''[[Berakhot (Talmud)|Berachot]]'', ''[[Shabbat (Talmud)|Shabbat]]'', and ''[[Moed|Eruvin]]'', which deal with practical [[Halakha|laws]], while others, such as ''[[Kodashim|Zevachim]]'' and ''[[Temurah (Talmud)|Temurah]]'', were hardly studied.<ref name=\"daf1\"/> Shapiro also viewed the program as a way to unify the Jewish people.<ref name=\"kollel\">Marks, Yehudah. \"It's Question Time at Daf Yomi Kollel: Jews from around the world can get instant answers \u2013 in English \u2013 to their questions on Gemara, halachah, and many other areas of Jewish interest\". ''Hamodia'', Israel News, 24 May 2012, pp. A30\u201331.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hevratpinto.org/tzadikim_eng/159_rabbi_meir_shapira.html |title=Rabbi Meir Shapira \u2013 The Rav of Lublin and Creator of Daf Yomi |publisher=Hevrat Pinto |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> His idea was greeted enthusiastically by the nearly 600 delegates at the Congress, including many [[Gadol|Torah leaders]] from Europe and America, who accepted it as a universal obligation for all Jews.<ref name=\"daf1\"/><ref>{{cite book |first=Yehoshua |last=Baumol |title=A Blaze in the Darkening Gloom: The life of Rav Meir Shapiro |publisher=Feldheim Publishers |year=1994 |isbn=0-87306-675-8|pages=161\u2013165}}</ref> The first cycle of Daf Yomi commenced on the first day of [[Rosh Hashanah]] 5684 (11 September 1923).<ref name=\"daf1\"/>\n\n===Process===\nWith 2,711 pages in the Talmud, one Daf Yomi cycle takes about 7 years, 5 months. The completion of each tractate is typically celebrated with a small [[siyum]], and the completion of the entire cycle is celebrated at an event known as the Siyum HaShas.\n\nDaf Yomi can be studied alone, with a ''[[chavrusa]]'' (study partner), in a daily ''shiur'' (class) led by a rabbi or teacher, via a telephone ''shiur'', [[CD-ROM]], or audio and online resources. Typically, Daf Yomi ''shiurim'' are held in [[synagogue]]s, yeshivas, and offices.<ref name=\"railroad\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewish-holiday.com/railroad.html |title=Tractates on Track: Learning on the railroad |first1=U. |last1=Heilman |first2=I. |last2=Lerner |work=Jewish Holiday Online |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525120656/http://www.jewish-holiday.com/railroad.html |archivedate=25 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They also take place in the [[United States Senate]], [[Wall Street]] board rooms,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJ5q6gsLSu0C&pg=PA165 |title= Understanding Jewish Holidays and Customs: Historical and Contemporary |first=Sol |last=Scharfstein |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |year=1999 |page=165 |isbn= 9780881256260}}</ref> and on the [[Long Island Rail Road]], in the last car of two [[Commuter rail|commuter trains]] departing [[Far Rockaway (LIRR station)|Far Rockaway]] at 7:51&nbsp;am and 8:15&nbsp;am, respectively, for [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"railroad\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/easy_riders_LGePszhvvWTBrJKnObKDEO |title=Easy Riders: Meet the 'commuter pals' who make trips to work cheery instead of dreary |first=Dana |last=Schuster |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[New York Post]]}}</ref><ref name=\"frand\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urwI7osBXmwC&pg=PA239|title=Listen To Your Messages: And other observations on contemporary Jewish life |first=Yissocher |last=Frand|authorlink=Yissocher Frand|publisher=Mesorah Publications Ltd. |year=1999 |page=239 |isbn=9781578191390}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/224223/video-photos-todays-historic-siyum-hashas-on-the-lirr.html|title=VIDEO & PHOTOS: Today\u2019s Historic Siyum HaShas On The LIRR|date=31 March 2014|accessdate=31 March 2014|work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper  \n|newspaper=[[The Jewish Press]]  |date=3 November 2006 |page=33\n|title=\"Shiur on LIRR completes Shas, Again |author=Shimon Golding\n|quote=Fifteen years ago ... and the rest is history. (For women on the 7:49 ... Tehillim..) ... Railroad personnel are well aware ... proud of the positive publicity ...}}</ref> Daf Yomi ''shiurim'' have been piped into the in-flight sound system of [[El Al]] flights.<ref name=\"frand\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urwI7osBXmwC&pg=PA239|title=Listen To Your Messages: And other observations on contemporary Jewish life |first=Yissocher |last=Frand|authorlink=Yissocher Frand|publisher=Mesorah Publications Ltd. |year=1999 |page=239 |isbn=9781578191390}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d34MAQAAMAAJ|journal=Midstream |volume=40 |publisher=Theodor Herzl Foundation |year=1994|page=44|title=Midstream }}</ref> A typical Daf Yomi ''shiur'' lasts one hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chareidi.org/archives5765/PKD65features.htm |title= Jews Around the Globe Celebrate Completion of Shas |author=Yated Ne'eman staff |date=9 March 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=Dei'ah VeDibur}}</ref> Participants study the text together with the commentary of [[Rashi]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uVIwAAAAYAAJ|title=Living with the Sages: Rashi and the Tosafists |first=Dovid |last=Castle |publisher=Feldheim Publishers |year=1996 |volume=1}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Schottenstein Edition of the Babylonian Talmud]], an English-language translation and interpretation published in 73 volumes between 1990 and 2004 by [[ArtScroll]],<ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web |url=http://jewishvoiceny.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=622:artscroll-set-to-release-digital-version-of-schottenstein-talmud&catid=93:art-a-culture&Itemid=276 |title=Artscroll Set to Release Digital Version of Schottenstein Talmud |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Baruch |last=Shubert |work=The Jewish Voice}}</ref> has been credited with significantly increasing the number of English-language participants in the Daf Yomi program.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vqsRAQAAIAAJ |title= The Jewish experience: 2,000 years: A collection of significant events |first=Nachman |last=Zakon |page=262 |publisher=Shaar Press |year=2005 |isbn= 9781578194964}}</ref> The Schottenstein Talmud has also been translated into Hebrew. Additional resources to assist those endeavoring to complete the cycle for the first time are audiotapes, online websites, and [[iPod]]s preloaded with lectures covering every page of the Talmud.<ref name=\"pod\">{{cite web |last=Mindlin |first=Alex |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B03E4DB133CF934A25750C0A9639C8B63 |title=2,000 Talmud Tapes, Or One Loaded IPod |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=17 March 2005 |accessdate=11 October 2007 |quote=Enter the ShasPod. For $399, Mr. Shmidman sends his customers a 20-gigabyte iPod loaded with Talmud lectures given by Rabbi Dovid Grossman of Los Angeles.}}</ref> The Dafyomi Advancement Forum, founded by [[Kollel]] Iyun Hadaf in 1996, is a free resource center offering English-language translations, outlines, charts, analyses and lectures on every ''daf'', as well as answers to any question by email.<ref name=\"kollel\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dafyomi.co.il/ |title=Kollel Iyun Hadaf, Authors of the Dafyomi Advancement Forum |publisher=dafyomi.co.il|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> Meoros HaDaf HaYomi, founded in 1999, disseminates a weekly Daf Yomi study sheet in both Hebrew and English available by email and regular mail. It has recorded ''shiurim'' on the ''daf'' on CD-ROM in English, Hebrew, Yiddish, and French.<ref>{{citation |url=http://jerusalemblueprint.com/events/results.aspx?tid=1 |pages=vii\u2013x |chapter=About Meoros HaDaf HaYomi |title=Meoros HaDaf HaYomi: A discussion of contemporary topics from Maseches Berachos |publisher=Feldheim Publishers |year=2005 |isbn=1-58330-789-3 |access-date=7 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427140341/http://jerusalemblueprint.com/events/results.aspx?tid=1 |archive-date=27 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Siyum HaShas program==\nAs with any siyum, the Siyum HaShas is both an end and a beginning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/m/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=17376 |title=Daf Yomi gathering unites Jews of all stripes |first=Avi |last=Shafran |authorlink=Avi Shafran |work=[[Washington Jewish Week]] |date=13 June 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130408083301/http://washingtonjewishweek.com/m/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=17376 |archivedate=8 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Dozens and even hundreds of [[Gadol|Gedolei Torah]] (Torah leaders) attend each Siyum HaShas. A distinguished [[Rav]] is honored with the recital of the last topic on the last page of Talmud and the saying of the ''[[Hadran (Talmud)|Hadran]]'' (\"We will return\") prayer. The Rav then delivers a scholarly lecture. Another honoree begins the new Daf Yomi cycle with the recital of the first topic on the first page of Talmud. Other rabbis are invited to deliver speeches on the Talmud and on the significance of the event. A special [[Kaddish]], the ''Kaddish Hagadol'', is also said. The program is rounded out with spirited singing and dancing.\n\n===1st Siyum HaShas===\nThe 1st Siyum HaShas took place on 2 February 1931 (15 [[Shevat]] 5691) in several cities in Europe and in [[Jerusalem]], with the main venue being the newly opened Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva in [[Lublin]], Poland. Tens of thousands of Jews attended these events. Rabbi Meir Shapiro presided over the Siyum in his yeshiva in the presence of many leaders of [[History of the Jews in Poland|Polish Jewry]].<ref name=\"daf2\">Shlomi, B. \"The Historic First Siyum HaShas\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 10 May 2012, pp. 12\u201313.</ref> In the United States, Siyums were held in [[Baltimore]] and [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\">Horowitz, Yisroel. \"Celebrating Siyum HaShas in America\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 21 June 2012, p. 3.</ref>\n\n===2nd Siyum HaShas===\nThe 2nd Siyum HaShas was held on 27 June 1938 (28 [[Sivan]] 5698). Again the main venue was the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva, but the founder of that yeshiva and the Daf Yomi program, Rabbi Meir Shapiro, was not present, having died suddenly in 1933 at the age of 46.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vosizneias.com/40348/2009/10/25/new-york-the-76th-yahrzeit-of-rav-meir-shapiro-zatzal-founder-of-the-daf-yomi/ |title=New York \u2013 The 76th Yahrzeit Of Rav Meir Shapiro zatzal Founder of The Daf Yomi |date=25 October 2009 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Yair |last=Hoffman |publisher=[[Vosizneias]]}}</ref> An estimated 15,000<ref name=\"daf3\"/> to 20,000<ref name=\"jta\"/> Jews came from all over Poland to celebrate the milestone together with many Torah luminaries, including the Rebbes of [[Boyan (Hasidic dynasty)|Boyan]]-Cracow, [[Sochatchov (Hasidic dynasty)|Sochatchov]], [[Sadigura (Hasidic dynasty)|Sadigura]], and [[Modzitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Modzhitz]], Rabbi [[Menachem Ziemba]], and Rabbi [[Dov Berish Weidenfeld]]. So many Gedolim were gathered in one place that many [[Halakha|halachic]] queries were sent directly to Lublin. The two-day event culminated with the completion of a [[Sefer Torah]] in memory of Shapiro.<ref name=\"daf3\">Shlomi, B. \"Daf Yomi: A lifeline as the Holocaust looms\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 17 May 2012, pp. 15\u201316.</ref>\n\nIn the United States, Siyums were held in Baltimore, Philadelphia, and [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\nIn [[Mandatory Palestine]], organizers planned to hold a Siyum in the Zikhron Meir neighborhood of [[Bnei Brak]] (named for Rabbi Meir Shapiro). It was cancelled at the last minute by the British mandatory government, which banned all mass gatherings for fear of \"anti-government demonstrations\".<ref name=\"daf3\"/>\n\n===3rd Siyum HaShas===\nThe 3rd Siyum HaShas was held on 19 November 1945 (14 [[Kislev]] 5706), with the main venues in [[Tel Aviv]], [[Haifa]], and Jerusalem. (The Siyum in Tel Aviv, attended by more than 3,000, was delayed one day due to the British-imposed [[curfew]].) Coming as it did after the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], this Siyum was dedicated to the memory of the millions of Jews who had perished.<ref name=try>Shlomi, B. \"Learning Torah in Trying Times\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 24 May 2012, pp. 15\u201316.</ref> A Siyum HaShas was also held in the [[displaced persons camp]] in [[Feldafing]], Germany, by a small group of survivors.<ref name=try/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aish.com/ho/p/48950676.html |title=The Day of My Victory |first=Joseph |last=Friedenson |author-link=Joseph Friedenson|date=27 March 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=[[Aish HaTorah|aish.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the Siyum was commemorated in the [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Boro Park]] section of Brooklyn, on [[West Side (Manhattan)|Manhattan's West Side]], and in [[Detroit]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\n===4th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 4th Siyum HaShas on 13 April 1953 (28 [[Nisan]] 5713) also had its main venue in Israel. An estimated 10,000 gathered for the main event in [[Mea Shearim]], following local siyums and speeches by leading rabbis in over half a dozen Jerusalem [[synagogue]]s.<ref name=\"daf4\">Shlomi, B. \"Public Displays of Kiddush Hashem\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 14 June 2012, pp. 20\u201321.</ref><ref name=\"Americanization\">Heilman, Samuel C. [https://books.google.com/books?id=c__ymBsbYdwC&pg=PA311 \"The Ninth Siyum HaShas: A case study in Orthodox contra-acculturation\"] in ''The Americanization of the Jews'', New York University Press, 1995, pp. 315\u2013338. {{ISBN|9780814780015}}</ref> Thousands attended the Siyum HaShas in Tel Aviv and danced afterwards at the central bus station. Well-attended Siyums also took place in Bnei Brak, [[Petah Tikva]], [[Haifa]], and [[Tiberias]].<ref name=\"daf4\"/>\n\nIn New York City, the 4th Siyum HaShas was celebrated at the [[National Council of Young Israel|Young Israel]] of [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]], as well as in [[Bensonhurst, Brooklyn|Bensonhurst]], [[Brownsville, Brooklyn|Brownsville]], [[West Side (Manhattan)|West Side of Manhattan]], and [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\n===5th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 5th Siyum HaShas took place on 5 September 1960 (13 [[Elul]] 5720). In Jerusalem's [[Kikar HaShabbat]], an open-air square at the intersection of the Mea Shearim and [[Geula]] neighborhoods, distinguished Torah leaders addressed the thousands of attendees. In Bnei Brak, police estimated an audience of between 12,000 and 15,000 in an outdoor field. Over 5,000 attended the Siyum in Tel Aviv, where Rabbi [[Yosef Shlomo Kahaneman]], the [[Ponevezh yeshiva|Ponevezher]] Rav, delivered a ''[[Hadran (Talmud)|hadran]]'' that lasted nearly two hours.<ref name=\"daf4\"/>\n\nIn the United States, Rabbi [[Aharon Kotler]] presided over the 5th Siyum HaShas at the Zeirei Agudas Yisroel convention in New York.<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/><ref name=wins>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/prime/ceo-coo-siyum/|title=The CEO, the COO and the Siyum|last=Borchardt|first=Reuvain|date=December 15, 2019|work=Hamodia|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Other Siyums took place in New York City and Baltimore.<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\n===6th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 6th Siyum HaShas was celebrated in many venues in Israel. The largest gatherings were at Jerusalem's [[International Convention Center (Jerusalem)|International Convention Center]] on 29 January 1968 (28 [[Tevet]] 5728), the Wagschal Hall in Bnei Brak, and the [[Fredric R. Mann Auditorium|Culture Palace]] in Tel Aviv (home of the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]]) on 30 January 1968. At the Tel Aviv event, the choirs of [[Ger (Hasidic dynasty)|Ger]], [[Vizhnitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Vizhnitz]], [[Modzitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Modzhitz]], and [[Chabad]], together with a [[Sephardic Jews|Sephardi]] boys choir and a Haredi Yerushalmi choir, performed between speeches.<ref name=\"daf6\">Shlomi, B. \"The Bnei Yeshiva Protect Us\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 21 June 2012, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\nIn London, the Agudath Israel of Britain organized a Siyum HaShas at the Town Hall in [[Stamford Hill]], attended by groups from [[Manchester]], [[Gateshead]], and [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]], and Agudath Israel leaders from Europe.<ref name=\"daf6\"/>\n\nThe largest Siyum HaShas to date in the United States took place on 28 January 1968<ref name=\"daf6\"/> at the [[Bais Yaakov]] of [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Boro Park]] with 300 people in attendance.<ref name=\"met\">{{cite web |url=http://www.5tjt.com/local-news/13311-metlife-stadium-to-build-a-mechitzah |title=MetLife Stadium To Build A Mechitzah |work=[[Five Towns Jewish Times]] |first=Rabbi Yishai |last=Cooper |date=16 February 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Other Siyums were held in New York City in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], the Bronx, the West Side of Manhattan, and Bensonhurst; Baltimore; [[Boston]]; [[Chicago]]; and [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"daf6\"/>\n\n===7th Siyum HaShas===\nTens of thousands of participants attended the 7th Siyum HaShas in Jerusalem, which was held on 23 June 1975 (14 [[Tammuz (Hebrew month)|Tammuz]] 5735). The event, which took place in the large courtyard of the Bais Yaakov High School, attracted thousands of religious schoolchildren wearing a special Daf Yomi badge, together with their teachers. Three hundred members of the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] were seated on the huge dais. The central celebration in Tel Aviv, again held at the Culture Palace and again featuring numerous choirs, also drew a huge attendance. In Bnei Brak, more than 10,000 people pressed into the Great Synagogue; the doors and some furnishings buckled under the crush of the crowd. After the ceremony and speeches, the crowd spilled out onto Rabbi Akiva Street for dancing. The Siyum was also marked in [[Netanya]], [[Safed]], [[Ramat Gan]], and, for the first time, in [[Giv'atayim]].<ref name=\"daf7\">Shlomi, B. \"Soldiers Defending Torah\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 28 June 2012, pp. 19\u201320.</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the 7th Siyum HaShas was held on 15 June 1975 at the [[Manhattan Center]] in New York City, drawing an audience of over 5,000.<ref name=\"daf7\"/><ref name=wins/> At this Siyum, the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah|Council of Torah Sages]] of Agudath Israel of America permanently dedicated the Siyum HaShas to the memory of the six million Jews murdered during the Holocaust.<ref name=\"Americanization\"/> Other Siyums took place in Philadelphia and [[Cleveland]]. Around the world, Siyums were held in [[England]], [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]], [[Brazil]], and [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"daf7\"/>\n\n===8th Siyum HaShas===\nThe mid-1970s and early 1980s saw an increase in the [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] population worldwide, fueling the growth of the Daf Yomi program and an increase in locations for the Siyum HaShas beginning with the 8th Siyum.<ref name=\"daf8\"/> At the conclusion of the eighth cycle of Daf Yomi, ''[[The New York Times]]'' estimated that 40,000 individuals worldwide had participated in the seven-and-a-half-year learning cycle.<ref>{{cite web |last=Austin |first=Charles |url=https://select.nytimes.com/search/restricted/article?res=F30B16FD3E5D0C768DDDA80994DA484D81 |title=Thousands Mark Talmudic Milestone |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 November 1982 |accessdate=11 October 2007|quote=\"This month marks the end of the study period during which, it is estimated, 40,000 Orthodox Jews around the world clustered around the ancient commentaries on the Scriptures\".}}</ref> According to Agudath Israel, close to 250,000 people worldwide participated in the 8th Siyum HaShas.<ref name=\"daf8\">Shlomi, B. \"For the Glory of Chareidi Jewry\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 5 July 2012, pp. 13\u201314.</ref> The largest attendance was in Israel, with 10,000 attendees at the [[Menora Mivtachim Arena|Yad Eliyahu Arena]] in Tel Aviv on 21 November 1982 (5 [[Kislev]] 5743), 10,000 at Jerusalem's International Convention Center, thousands in Bnei Brak at Wagschal Hall, and hundreds in Haifa, Petah Tikva, and, for the first time, in [[Ashdod]]. At the Jerusalem event, a special certificate was awarded to four men who had completed all eight cycles of Daf Yomi.<ref name=\"daf8\"/>\n\nThe main Siyum HaShas in the United States was celebrated on 14 November 1982 at the [[Felt Forum]] in New York City, with over 5,000 participants.<ref name=\"klass\"/><ref name=\"Americanization\"/> This program was broadcast to gatherings in Chicago, Los Angeles, [[Toronto]], and Montreal. Other Siyums took place in Detroit; Cleveland; and [[Monsey, New York]].<ref name=\"daf8\"/>\n\n===9th Siyum HaShas===\n[[File:Madison Square Garden Transformation Stage 1.jpg|right|thumb|[[Madison Square Garden]], site of the 9th, 10th, and 11th Siyum HaShas in New York.]]\nAt the Agudath Israel of America convention following the 8th Siyum HaShas in New York, Agudah chairman Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]] announced that he wished to book [[Madison Square Garden]] for the next Siyum HaShas, to be held on 26 April 1990. Many were skeptical that the stadium, seating 20,000, could be filled, considering that the 8th Siyum HaShas in New York had attracted only 5,000. But Agudath Israel of America went ahead and paid a nonrefundable deposit two and a half years in advance of the Siyum, and attendance met all expectations, with over 20,000 in attendance.<ref name=\"klass\"/><ref name=\"met\"/><ref name=\"daf9\"/> Tickets on the main floor, priced at $100 apiece, were sold out for weeks in advance, and the women's section was also sold out.<ref name=\"Americanization\"/> Other Siyums were held in Baltimore, Chicago, Cleveland, Los Angeles, Toronto, Montreal, and Tel Aviv.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qOgCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA15 ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]''], 17 February 1997, pp. 15\u201316.</ref>\n\nEnormous crowds were seen at the 9th Siyum HaShas in Israel's main cities on 24 April 1990 (29 Nisan 5750). These included a Siyum in Tel Aviv at the [[Menora Mivtachim Arena|Yad Eliyahu Arena]], a Siyum in Jerusalem in the spacious Bais Yaakov High School courtyard, and a Siyum in Bnei Brak. Special children's Siyums were also held in Jerusalem (with students from 84 [[Talmud Torah]]s and schools in attendance) and in Bnei Brak (with 5,000 children together with leading rabbis and educators in attendance).<ref name=\"daf9\">Shlomi, B. \"An Extraordinary Kiddush Hashem\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 12 July 2012, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\nThe 9th Siyum HaShas in [[London]] drew a large audience and lasted six hours, followed by a festive meal. Smaller events took place in Manchester, Gateshead, and among local Daf Yomi groups in England. In [[Melbourne]], Australia, home to eight regular Daf Yomi ''shiurim'', the central Siyum HaShas drew 1,000 people.<ref name=\"daf9\"/>\n\n===10th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 10th Siyum HaShas in the United States took place on 28 September 1997 at two New York City locations: [[Madison Square Garden]], with an audience of 25,000, and the [[Nassau Coliseum]], with an audience of 20,000.<ref name=\"klass\"/> Siyums were also held in [[Boston]], Cleveland, [[Chicago]], Los Angeles, [[Pittsburgh]], and [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]],<ref name=\"daf10\"/> bringing total U.S. participation to 70,000 individuals.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zjfPA1NZFbgC&pg=PR19 |page=xix |title=The World of the Yeshiva: An intimate portrait of Orthodox Jewry |first=William B. |last=Helmreich |year=2000 |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |isbn= 9780881256413}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IEoMEW8Xy5wC&pg=PA9510|title= Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the 105th Congress Second Session|volume=144 \u2013 Part 7 |publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]] |year=1998 |page=9510}}</ref> Siyums also took place in Toronto, Ontario and Montreal, Quebec in Canada, and Melbourne, Australia.<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nIn Israel, the central Siyum HaShas was held at Tel Aviv's Yad Eliyahu Arena on 28 September 1997 (26 [[Elul]] 5757) with thousands in attendance, and was broadcast live to other locations. The honor of starting the new cycle of Daf Yomi went to Rabbi [[Shmuel Wosner]], a student of Rabbi Meir Shapiro, who shared his memories of the first Siyum HaShas in 1931. The [[Shabbat]] preceding this Siyum was billed as \"Shabbos Daf Yomi\", with rabbis calling on Israelis to increase their study of Daf Yomi. Other Siyums were held in [[Beth midrash|battei medrash]] (study halls) in Jerusalem and Bnei Brak, and in Ramat [[Vizhnitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Vizhnitz]] in Haifa.<ref name=\"daf10\">Shlomi, B. \"Holy Torah, Plead for Us\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 2 August 2012, pp. 12\u201322.</ref>\n\nIn England, the central Siyum HaShas was held in the Sobel Center in London, drawing thousands of attendees. Over 2,500 attended the ''[[seudat mitzvah]]'' (celebratory meal) hosted by Agudath Israel in London. Another thousand attended Siyums in Manchester and Gateshead.<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\n===11th Siyum HaShas===\nAn estimated 300,000 people worldwide participated in the 11th Siyum HaShas.<ref name=\"jta\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/12522/Celebrationofdaily |title=Daf Yomi program has Polish roots |first=Carolyn |last=Slutsky |date=30 November 1999 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415041722/http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/12522/Celebrationofdaily |archivedate=15 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The largest celebrations were held on 1 March 2005 in three locations in the New York area: Madison Square Garden, the [[Continental Airlines Arena]] in [[New Jersey]], and the [[Jacob K. Javits Convention Center]], with a combined 45,000 attendees.<ref name=\"klass\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Newman |first=Andy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/02/nyregion/02talmud.html |title=Orthodox Jews Celebrate End of a True Sabbatical |work=The New York Times |date=2 March 2005 |accessdate=11 October 2007}}</ref> Portions of each program were telecast to the other sites and to more than 50 locations countrywide,<ref name=\"daf10\"/> including the [[Rosemont Theatre]] in Chicago, the [[Walt Disney Concert Hall]] in Los Angeles, and the [[Ricoh Coliseum]] in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.torah.org/features/spirfocus/siyumhashas.html# |title=The Secret of the Jews |first=Rabbi Avi |last=Shafran |authorlink=Avi Shafran |year=2005 |publisher=torah.org |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050310014240/http://www.torah.org/features/spirfocus/siyumhashas.html |archivedate=10 March 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The programs were also broadcast to 20 overseas locations.<ref name=\"daf10\"/> The honor of reciting the final portion of the final page at the Continental Arena event was given to Rabbi Chaim Stein, [[rosh yeshiva]] of the [[Telshe yeshiva]] of [[Wickliffe, Ohio]], who was making his ninth personal Siyum HaShas<ref name=\"daf10\"/> and had participated in each of the ten preceding events, including the first one held at the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva in 1931.<ref>{{cite web |last=Goldfeder |first=Moshe |url=http://media.www.yucommentator.com/media/storage/paper652/news/2005/03/08/News/Eleventh.Siyum.Hashas.Hosts.Record.Breaking.Turnout-885612.shtml |title=Eleventh Siyum Hashas Hosts Record Breaking Turnout |work=The Commentator |publisher=[[Yeshiva University]] |date=8 March 2005 |accessdate=11 October 2007 |quote=\"The climax of the evening, the actual completion of the Talmud achieved by the reading of the last line, was performed in New Jersey by Rabbi Chaim Stein, head of the Telshe Yeshiva of Wickliffe. Rabbi Stein has the distinction of having participated in every Siyum HaShas since the very first, way back in Poland, 1931\". |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070701223222/http://media.www.yucommentator.com/media/storage/paper652/news/2005/03/08/News/Eleventh.Siyum.Hashas.Hosts.Record.Breaking.Turnout-885612.shtml |archivedate=1 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Israel, 10,000 tickets prepared for the central Siyum HaShas at Yad Eliyahu Arena in Tel Aviv on 1 March 2005 (20 [[Adar]] I, 5765) sold out immediately. The proceedings were viewed by live satellite hookup in Jerusalem, Bnei Brak, and Ashdod. Siyums were also held in Jerusalem at the International Convention Center, in the [[Zikhron Moshe]] synagogue, in the [[Pinsk-Karlin (Hasidic dynasty)|Pinsk-Karlin]] ''beis medrash'', in [[Kiryat Belz]], and at the [[Erlau (Hasidic dynasty)|Erlau]] yeshiva. An English-language Siyum at the Jerusalem Convention Center was attended by the Rebbes of [[Boyan (Hasidic dynasty)|Boyan]], [[Karlin-Stolin (Hasidic dynasty)|Karlin-Stolin]], [[Kaliv (Hasidic dynasty)|Kaliv]], and [[Pittsburg (Hasidic dynasty)|Pittsburg]], as well as by English-speaking roshei yeshiva Rabbi [[Nosson Tzvi Finkel (Mir)|Nosson Tzvi Finkel]], Rabbi [[Chaim Pinchas Scheinberg]], Rabbi Yitzchak Sheiner, and Rabbi [[Mendel Weinbach]]. Other Siyums were held in Bnei Brak, Haifa, Ashdod, Netanya, Petah Tikva, [[Rehovot]], [[Kokhav Ya'akov|Tel Zion]], and [[Kiryat Ata]].<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nThe 11th Siyum HaShas was also celebrated by 4,000 people in London,<ref name=\"daf10\"/> 2,000 people in Manchester,<ref name=\"daf10\"/> and at events in [[Antwerp]],<ref name=\"daf10\"/> and Melbourne and Sydney, Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chareidi.org/archives5765/vayakhel/aaustrlvyk65.htm |title=Gala Siyum HaShas in Melbourne Australia |date=2 March 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=Dei'ah VeDibur |author=Yated Ne'eman Australian correspondent}}</ref> The scope of celebrations marking the 11th Siyum HaShas was described in one newspaper account as follows:\n<blockquote>Among the [U.S.] cities where Siyums were held were [[Atlanta]], Baltimore, Boston, [[Dallas]], [[Detroit]], [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]], [[Denver]], [[Houston]], Los Angeles, [[Lakewood, New Jersey|Lakewood]], [[Miami]], [[Milwaukee]], [[New Orleans]], [[St. Louis]], [[Seattle]], [[Cincinnati]], [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, Cleveland, and Chicago.</blockquote>\n<blockquote>Siyums were also held in [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada; [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina; [[Caracas]], Venezuela; [[Sao Paulo]], Brazil; [[Santiago]], Chile; [[Johannesburg]], South Africa; [[Lublin]], Poland, [[Moscow]], [[Saint Petersburg|St. Petersburg]], [[Kiev]], and [[Odessa]] in the [[Former Soviet Union]]; [[Hong Kong]], China; and [[Sydney]], Australia.<ref name=\"daf10\"/></blockquote>\n\nComing as it did the day before the [[Bereavement in Judaism#Yahrtzeit, Nahala|yahrzeit]] of Hasidic master Reb [[Elimelech of Lizensk]], when hundreds traditionally make a pilgrimage to his grave in [[Le\u017cajsk]], Poland, two Siyums were celebrated in Poland, including the first at the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva since 1931 (see below). A large group from Israel traveled to the former ''beis medrash'' of the Gerrer Rebbes in [[G\u00f3ra Kalwaria]]. A Siyum HaShas was made in [[Moscow]] by the united Jewish communities in Russia under the leadership of Chief Rabbi [[Berel Lazar]].<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nThe 11th Siyum HaShas was also marked by an event for non-[[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] Jews called Jewish Unity Live 2005. The central venue, the [[New Jersey Performing Arts Center]], featured [[Elie Wiesel]], U.S. Senator [[Joe Lieberman|Joseph Lieberman]], and other celebrities; gatherings were also held on college campuses and military bases across the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/features/same_page  |title=On the Same Page |date=25 February 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Steve |last=Lipman |work=[[The Jewish Week]]}}</ref>\n\n===12th Siyum HaShas===\n[[File:New Meadowlands Stadium Mezz Corner.jpg|right|thumb|[[MetLife Stadium]], site of the 12th and 13th Siyum HaShas]]\nThe [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], which has seating for 82,500, was the main U.S. venue for the 12th Siyum HaShas on 1 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/General+News/135894/BREAKING-NEWS%3A-Siyum-HaShas-WILL-Take-Place-In-MetLife-Stadium-Despite-Weather-Reports-%5BUPDATED-INFO%5D.html |title=BREAKING NEWS: Siyum HaShas WILL Take Place In MetLife Stadium Despite Weather Reports|date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=2 August 2012 |work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref> An additional 8,500 folding chairs were placed on the playing field, and a dais of approximately 500 seats accommodated [[Admor]]im, [[rosh yeshiva|roshei yeshiva]], and distinguished rabbis. An additional section of 1,000 seats was reserved for teachers of Daf Yomi ''shiurim''.<ref name=\"nj\">{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-news/nearly-100-000-jews-to-gather-in-n-j-to-celebrate-completion-of-talmud-cycle.premium-1.454493 |title=Nearly 100,000 Jews to gather in N.J. to celebrate completion of Talmud cycle |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=1 August 2012 |first=Debra |last=Nussbaum Cohen |work=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref><ref name=\"july\">{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/will-rav-shteinman-be-attending-the-siyum-hashas-at-metlife-stadium |title=Will Rav Shteinman Be Attending the Siyum Hashas at MetLife Stadium? |first=Casriel |last=Bauman |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=22 July 2012 |publisher=matzav.com}}</ref> All 92,000 seats were sold out.<ref name=\"sold\">{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/all-93000-tickets-sold-siyum-hashas-to-be-largest-event-ever-at-metlife-stadium |title=All 93,000 Tickets Sold: Siyum Hashas to Be Largest Event Ever at MetLife Stadium |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2012 |publisher=matzav.com |first=Casriel |last=Bauman}}</ref> A total of 2,200 [[Plasma display|plasma screens]] were set up inside the stadium and four [[Jumbotron]] screens were positioned outside the stadium for overflow attendees. Female attendees, who constituted an estimated 20 percent of the crowd, were seated in the upper deck of the stadium behind a {{convert|12|ft|adj=on}} high, {{convert|2.5|mi|adj=on}} long ''[[mechitza]]'' (curtain divider) that was drawn during prayers.<ref name=\"nj\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hwIi1pRFQMRR-ROz7eCSJ-eKPn9g?docId=aa385adeba904f3a991a17bf0c8d037f |title=NJ's MetLife Stadium site of Talmud celebration |first=Kate |last=Zezima |date=1 August 2012 |accessdate=1 August 2012 |publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Satellite broadcasts and web feeds were piped to over 100 locations, including those in Chicago, Baltimore, Toronto, Montreal, Los Angeles, Mexico City, Uruguay, Buenos Aires, Argentina, Melbourne, Hong Kong, and Lublin, Poland.<ref name=\"sold\"/>\n\nFor the first time, a [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] Siyum HaShas was also held, on 6 August 2012, at [[Congregation Shearith Israel]] on Manhattan's [[Upper West Side]].<ref name=\"nj\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/2012/06/27/3099366/ny-modern-orthodox-institutions-to-celebrate-siyum-hashas |title=N.Y. Modern Orthodox institutions to celebrate Siyum HaShas |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701071529/http://www.jta.org/news/article/2012/06/27/3099366/ny-modern-orthodox-institutions-to-celebrate-siyum-hashas |archivedate=1 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/controversial-chovevei-torah-rosh-yeshiva-rabbi-linzer-to-address-modern-orthodox-siyum-hashas-also-featuring-female-mesaymim |first=Casriel |last=Bauman |publisher=matzav.com |title=Controversial Chovevei Torah Rosh Yeshiva Rabbi Linzer to Address 'Modern Orthodox' Siyum Hashas Also Featuring Female Mesaymim |date=5 July 2012 |accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> This event featured lectures on various aspects of both the Jerusalem and the Babylonian Talmud, and participation by female Torah scholars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siyumhashas12.com |title=NYC Modern Orthodox Siyum HaShas website |first=Dov |last=Weinstock |date=17 July 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120708230422/http://siyumhashas12.com/ |archivedate=8 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTens of thousands attended Siyums in Israel. These included the [[Dirshu]] World Siyum at the [[Menora Mivtachim Arena|Yad Eliyahu Arena]] in Tel Aviv, the National Siyum HaShas in [[Petah Tikva]], a Siyum organized by Agudath Israel and [[Degel HaTorah]] in the [[French Hill]] neighborhood of Jerusalem, and a Siyum organized by the [[Shas]] political party at [[Teddy Stadium]] in Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.5tjt.com/international-news/14315-dirshu-world-siyum-48-hours-of-achdus-simcha-and-accomplishment |title=Dirshu World Siyum: 48 hours of achdus, simcha, and accomplishment |work=[[Five Towns Jewish Times]] |first=Yonoson |last=Klein |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/157387 |title=Preparations Underway for Siyum HaShas in Tel Aviv |date=1 July 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Hana Levi |last=Julian |work=[[Arutz Sheva|Israel National News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/article.php?p=130807 |title=Jerusalem City Hall Says 'NO' to Funding Siyum HaShas for Shas |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref> There were two English-language Siyums at [[International Convention Center (Jerusalem)|Jerusalem's International Convention Center]], one sponsored by Dirshu on 31 July<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/157553 |title=Final Preparations for Dirshu's English Siyum HaShas |first=Gil |last=Ronen |work=[[Arutz Sheva]] |date=5 July 2012 |accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref> and one organized by Kollel Iyun Hadaf on 5 August.<ref name=\"kollel\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishpress.com/news/israel/behind-the-plans-for-jerusalem-siyum-hashas-celebration/2012/01/11/ |title=Behind The Plans For Jerusalem Siyum Hashas Celebration |first=Steve K. |last=Walz |date=11 January 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[The Jewish Press]]}}</ref> The various Religious Zionist organizations sponsored a separate siyum at the same Convention Center on 2 August, and there was another English language siyum at Jerusalem's Great Synagogue on 9 August.\n\nA new edition of the Talmud was launched to coincide with the 12th Siyum HaShas by [[Koren Publishers]]. Known as the Koren Talmud Bavli, this edition features translation and commentary by Rabbi [[Adin Steinsaltz]]. The project, slated to be 42 volumes, is overseen by Rabbi Dr. [[Tzvi Hersh Weinreb]] who serves as editor-in-chief.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jta.org/2012/09/10/life-religion/siyum-hashas-inspiring-newcomers-to-daily-talmud-study|title=Siyum HaShas inspiring newcomers to daily Talmud study |work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |first=Neil |last=Rubin |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===13th Siyum HaShas===\n[[File:13th Siyum HaShas 2019.jpg|thumb|13th Siyum HaShas in MetLife Stadium.]]\n[[File:Dirshu Siyum Hashas NY 2020.jpg|thumb|[[Dirshu]] Siyum HaShas on February 9, 2020, in the [[Prudential Center]], [[Newark, New Jersey]]]]\nFor the 13th Siyum HaShas, whose study cycle concluded on the 7th of [[Tevet]] 5780 (January 4, 2020), celebrations were scheduled to take place in locations in the U.S., Europe, Israel, and other countries, in January and February 2020. The main event in the United States, staged by [[Agudath Israel of America]], took place on January 1 at [[MetLife Stadium]], which has capacity for 92,000 seats, with a second location at [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn, NY]].<ref name=wins/> Concerned about holding an outdoor event during the [[New Jersey]] winter, planners had proposed holding the main siyum in five different indoor venues in New York, New Jersey, and Philadelphia simultaneously with [[live streaming]] hook-ups between them.<ref name=wins/> But the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah#In the United States|Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] of Agudath Israel of America opted to hold the siyum in one place based on the principle of ''[[b'rov am hadrat melech]]'', that God's honor is increased when a large number of Jews gather in the same place.<ref name=wins/>\n\nEarly Siyum HaShas celebrations also took place in December 2019 in [[Melbourne]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/2019/12/17/melbourne-holds-siyum-hashas/|title=Melbourne Holds Siyum HaShas|date=December 17, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019|work=Hamodia}}</ref> and [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/2019/12/23/siyum-hashas-held-vienna-austria/|title=Siyum HaShas Held in Vienna, Austria|first=Rivka|last=Junger|date=December 23, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019|work=Hamodia}}</ref>\n\nIn Israel, the Hadran organization organized a Siyum HaShas celebration focussing on women's learning and teaching of Talmud in general and the Daf Yomi in particular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/life/437804/thousands-gather-to-celebrate-womens-talmud-study-in-jerusalem/|title=Thousands gather to celebrate women\u2019s Talmud study in Jerusalem|last=Blumberg|first=Ilana|date=January 6, 2020|website=The Forward|publisher=The Jewish Forward|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n[[Dirshu]] held their own Siyum in the [[Prudential Center]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]] on February 9, 2020.\n\n==Return to Lublin==\nWith the closure of the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva by the Nazis and the conversion of the yeshiva to a medical academy, the Siyum HaShas was not held in its original venue for many cycles. In 1998 the yeshiva was returned to the Jewish community of [[Warsaw]], which undertook renovations.<ref name=\"jta\"/> In March 2005, Rabbi David Singer, an Orthodox Jew from [[Brooklyn]], New York, whose father, Rabbi Joseph Singer, the [[Pilzno (Hasidic dynasty)#Rabbi Joseph Singer|Pilzno]] Rav, had been born in Poland,<ref>Friedman, C. \"The Grave of the Koloshitzer Rav, Hy\"d\". ''[[Hamodia]]'' Features, 22 November 2012, p. C2</ref> organized the 11th Siyum HaShas in the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva.<ref name=\"jta\"/><ref name=ami>Krausz, Yossi. \"Time Traveler\". ''Ami'', 13 June 2012, pp. 54\u201363.</ref> Chaired by Rabbi [[Baruch Taub]], rabbi emeritus of [[Beth Avraham Yoseph of Toronto]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ou.org/torah/author/Rabbi_Baruch_Taub |title=Rabbi Baruch Taub |publisher=[[Orthodox Union]] |year=2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528171719/http://www.ou.org/torah/author/Rabbi_Baruch_Taub |archivedate=28 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the event was linked by satellite to the one in New York and was attended by over 200 participants,<ref name=\"jta\"/> including the Rebbes of [[Sadigura (Hasidic dynasty)|Sadigura]], [[Modzitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Modzhitz]], [[Nadvorna (Hasidic dynasty)|Nadvorna]], and [[Biala (Hasidic dynasty)|Biala]]; Rabbi [[Yona Metzger]], [[Chief Rabbinate of Israel|Chief Rabbi of Israel]], and Israeli politician Rabbi [[Menachem Porush]].<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nSinger organized the 12th Siyum HaShas at the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva on 1 August 2012. Participants viewed a simultaneous broadcast from the event taking place that same day at the [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[New Jersey]].<ref name=\"nesivos\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nesivos.com/index.php/siyum-hashas-lublin-2/ |title=Siyum HaShas Lublin & Poland Tour |publisher=nesivos.com |year=2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625103239/http://www.nesivos.com/index.php/siyum-hashas-lublin-2 |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\n''Siyum HaShas'' also refers to any individual's or group's [[Siyum|completion]] of all 2,711 [[List of masechtot, chapters, mishnahs and pages in the Talmud|pages of Talmud]]. Many rabbis and Torah scholars have completed the study of the entire Talmud one or more times in their lifetimes.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dEoW-Q_Wq2AC&pg=PA186  |title=The Maggid Speaks: Favorite Stories and Parables of Rabbi Sholom Schwadron, Shlita, Maggid of Jerusalem |last1=Krohn |first1=Paysach J. |authorlink1=Paysach Krohn |last2=Schwadron |first2=Shalom |authorlink2=Shalom Schwadron |publisher=Mesorah Publications Ltd. |year=1987 |isbn= 9780899062303|page=186}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-Jb4w78HMzUC&pg=PA445 |title=The Legacy of Maran Rav Aharon Kotler: A vivid portrait of the teachings, qualities, and accomplishments of the venerable rosh hayeshiva |page=445 |first=Yitzchok |last=Dershowitz |publisher=[[Feldheim Publishers]] |isbn= 9781583308752|year=2005}}</ref> Synagogues, organizations, and community groups also complete the Talmud on a yearly basis, marking an annual Siyum HaShas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/4564767/jewish/What-Is-a-Siyum-Hashas.htm|title=What Is a Siyum HaShas?|work=[[Chabad|Chabad.org]]|year=2019|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.5tjt.com/inwood-celebrates-second-annual-siyum-hashas\n|title=Inwood Celebrates Second Annual Siyum HaShas|work=Five Towns Jewish Times |date=29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n|title=Leadership And A Vision For The Future: RAA's 29th Annual Siyum HaShas\n|url=http://www.5tjt.com/leadership-vision-future-raas-29th-annual-siyum-hashas|work=Five Towns Jewish Times| date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref> An initiative known as a Shas-A-Thon brings hundreds and even thousands of participants together to study and complete the entire Talmud in one day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/2018/12/31/entire-shas-finished-one-day-yerushalayim/|title=Entire Shas Finished on One Day in Yerushalayim|date=December 31, 2018|accessdate=December 25, 2019|work=Hamodia}}</ref> This initiative is sometimes used as a fund-raiser, with participants collecting pledges from donors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://shasathon.org/5780/index.html|title=Bringing Hope Through Torah|publisher=ATIME Shas-A-Thon|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of masechtot, chapters, mishnahs and pages in the Talmud]]\n* [[Talmud]]\n* [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commonscat|Siyum HaShas}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thesiyum.org The Siyum Official website]\n*[https://vimeo.com/65770304 Video Highlights of 12th Siyum HaShas in MetLife Stadium]\n*[http://www.vosizneias.com/111068/2012/08/01/east-rutherford-nj-photos-throughout-evening-of-whats-happening Photos of the 12th Siyum HaShas in MetLife Stadium]\n*[http://www.chareidi.org/archives5765/PKD65features.htm \"Jews Around the Globe Celebrate Completion of Shas\"] Overview of events celebrating the 11th Siyum HaShas\n*[https://shiur.com/category.php?cat=siyum-hashas Collection of Siyum HaShas Videos over the years] \n \n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States|Communal activities}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siyum HaShas}}\n[[Category:Talmud]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Poland]]\n[[he:\u05d4\u05d3\u05e3 \u05d4\u05d9\u05d5\u05de\u05d9]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|celebration of the completion of the Daf Yomi}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name              = Siyum HaShas\n|native_name       = {{Nobold|{{Hebrew|\u05e1\u05d9\u05d5\u05dd \u05d4\u05e9\"\u05e1}}}}\n|native_name_lang  = Hebrew\n|logo              = Siyum logo.png\n|logo_alt          = \n|logo_caption      = Logo of the main Siyum HaShas organized by [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n|logo_size         = \n|image             =\n|image_size        = \n|alt               = \n|caption           = Audience view of the 12th Siyum HaShas at [[MetLife Stadium]]\n|status            = Active\n|genre             = \n|date              = \n|frequency         = Every 2,711 days\n|venue             = International\n|location          = \n|coordinates       = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|type:event|display=inline,title}} --> \n|country           = \n|years_active      = {{age|1923|9|11}} \n|first             = {{start date|df=yes|1931|02|02}}\n|founder_name      = Rabbi [[Meir Shapiro]]\n|last              = \n|prev              = January 1, 2020\n|next              = June 7, 2027\n|participants      = \n|attendance        = 92,000\n|capacity          =\n|area              = \n|budget            = \n|activity          = \n|leader_name       =\n|patron            = \n|organized         = [[World Agudath Israel]]\n|filing            = \n|people            = \n|member            = \n|sponsor           = <!-- | or sponsors = -->\n|current           = \n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Siyum HaShas''' ({{lang-he|\u05e1\u05d9\u05d5\u05dd \u05d4\u05e9\"\u05e1}}, lit. \"completion of the Six Orders [of the Talmud]\") is a celebration of the completion of the [[Daf Yomi]] (daily [[Talmud]] folio) program, a roughly seven-and-a-half-year cycle of learning the Oral [[Torah]] and its commentaries, in which each of the 2,711 pages of the Babylonian Talmud are covered in sequence - one page per day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/siyum-hashas-ad-campaign-commences-ticket-info-to-be-available-after-sukkos |title=Siyum Hashas Ad Campaign Commences, Ticket Info to Be Available After Sukkos |first=Shmiel |last=Gellman |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |publisher=matzav.com}}</ref> The first Daf Yomi cycle began on the first day of [[Rosh Hashanah]] 5684 (11 September 1923); the thirteenth cycle concluded on January 4, 2020 and the fourteenth cycle began the following day, to be concluded on June 7, 2027. The Siyum HaShas marks both the end of the previous cycle and the beginning of the next, and is characterized by inspiring speeches and rousing singing and dancing.\n\nFor Jews for whom [[Torah study]] is a daily obligation, the publicity and excitement surrounding the Siyum HaShas has resulted in more participants, more Daf Yomi ''[[Shiur (Torah)|shiurim]]'' (lessons), and more Siyum locations with each cycle.<ref name=\"daf7\"/> Since 1990, attendance at the main Siyum HaShas in America, organized by the [[Agudath Israel of America]], has increased dramatically, necessitating the booking of larger arenas and stadiums.<ref name=\"klass\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishpress.com/sections/community/upcoming-events/the-twelfth-siyum-hashas-of-daf-yomi/2012/07/26/ |title=The Twelfth Siyum HaShas Of Daf Yomi|first=Rabbi Yaakov |last=Klass |work=[[The Jewish Press]] |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref> The 13th Siyum HaShas on January 1, 2020 took place in [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[New Jersey]] with a sellout crowd of over 90,000. Other organizations, such as [[Dirshu]], and neighborhood groups and [[synagogues]] in cities around the world, also hold Siyum HaShas events expected to attract tens of thousands of participants.\n\n==Background==\n{{main article|Daf Yomi}}\n[[File:Meir Shapiro.jpg|thumb|upright|Rabbi Meir Shapiro, initiator of Daf Yomi.]]\nThe novel idea of Jews in all parts of the world studying the same ''daf''<ref>A ''daf'', or ''blatt'' in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], consists of both sides of the page.</ref> each day, with the goal of completing the entire Talmud, was put forth at the First World Congress of the [[World Agudath Israel]] in [[Vienna]] on 16 August 1923 by Rabbi [[Meir Shapiro]], then [[Rav]] of [[Sanok]], Poland, and future [[rosh yeshiva]] of the [[Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva]].<ref name=\"daf1\">Shlomi, B. \"A Brilliant Idea: Daf Yomi\". ''[[Hamodia]]'' Magazine, 3 May 2012, pp. 18\u201320.</ref> In those years, only some of the 63 tractates of the Talmud were being studied regularly, such as ''[[Berakhot (Talmud)|Berachot]]'', ''[[Shabbat (Talmud)|Shabbat]]'', and ''[[Moed|Eruvin]]'', which deal with practical [[Halakha|laws]], while others, such as ''[[Kodashim|Zevachim]]'' and ''[[Temurah (Talmud)|Temurah]]'', were hardly studied.<ref name=\"daf1\"/> Shapiro also viewed the program as a way to unify the Jewish people.<ref name=\"kollel\">Marks, Yehudah. \"It's Question Time at Daf Yomi Kollel: Jews from around the world can get instant answers \u2013 in English \u2013 to their questions on Gemara, halachah, and many other areas of Jewish interest\". ''Hamodia'', Israel News, 24 May 2012, pp. A30\u201331.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hevratpinto.org/tzadikim_eng/159_rabbi_meir_shapira.html |title=Rabbi Meir Shapira \u2013 The Rav of Lublin and Creator of Daf Yomi |publisher=Hevrat Pinto |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> His idea was greeted enthusiastically by the nearly 600 delegates at the Congress, including many [[Gadol|Torah leaders]] from Europe and America, who accepted it as a universal obligation for all Jews.<ref name=\"daf1\"/><ref>{{cite book |first=Yehoshua |last=Baumol |title=A Blaze in the Darkening Gloom: The life of Rav Meir Shapiro |publisher=Feldheim Publishers |year=1994 |isbn=0-87306-675-8|pages=161\u2013165}}</ref> The first cycle of Daf Yomi commenced on the first day of [[Rosh Hashanah]] 5684 (11 September 1923).<ref name=\"daf1\"/>\n\n===Process===\nWith 2,711 pages in the Talmud, one Daf Yomi cycle takes about 7 years, 5 months. The completion of each tractate is typically celebrated with a small [[siyum]], and the completion of the entire cycle is celebrated at an event known as the Siyum HaShas.\n\nDaf Yomi can be studied alone, with a ''[[chavrusa]]'' (study partner), in a daily ''shiur'' (class) led by a rabbi or teacher, via a telephone ''shiur'', [[CD-ROM]], or audio and online resources. Typically, Daf Yomi ''shiurim'' are held in [[synagogue]]s, yeshivas, and offices.<ref name=\"railroad\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewish-holiday.com/railroad.html |title=Tractates on Track: Learning on the railroad |first1=U. |last1=Heilman |first2=I. |last2=Lerner |work=Jewish Holiday Online |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525120656/http://www.jewish-holiday.com/railroad.html |archivedate=25 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They also take place in the [[United States Senate]], [[Wall Street]] board rooms,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJ5q6gsLSu0C&pg=PA165 |title= Understanding Jewish Holidays and Customs: Historical and Contemporary |first=Sol |last=Scharfstein |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |year=1999 |page=165 |isbn= 9780881256260}}</ref> and on the [[Long Island Rail Road]], in the last car of two [[Commuter rail|commuter trains]] departing [[Far Rockaway (LIRR station)|Far Rockaway]] at 7:51&nbsp;am and 8:15&nbsp;am, respectively, for [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"railroad\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/easy_riders_LGePszhvvWTBrJKnObKDEO |title=Easy Riders: Meet the 'commuter pals' who make trips to work cheery instead of dreary |first=Dana |last=Schuster |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[New York Post]]}}</ref><ref name=\"frand\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urwI7osBXmwC&pg=PA239|title=Listen To Your Messages: And other observations on contemporary Jewish life |first=Yissocher |last=Frand|authorlink=Yissocher Frand|publisher=Mesorah Publications Ltd. |year=1999 |page=239 |isbn=9781578191390}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/224223/video-photos-todays-historic-siyum-hashas-on-the-lirr.html|title=VIDEO & PHOTOS: Today\u2019s Historic Siyum HaShas On The LIRR|date=31 March 2014|accessdate=31 March 2014|work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper  \n|newspaper=[[The Jewish Press]]  |date=3 November 2006 |page=33\n|title=\"Shiur on LIRR completes Shas, Again |author=Shimon Golding\n|quote=Fifteen years ago ... and the rest is history. (For women on the 7:49 ... Tehillim..) ... Railroad personnel are well aware ... proud of the positive publicity ...}}</ref> Daf Yomi ''shiurim'' have been piped into the in-flight sound system of [[El Al]] flights.<ref name=\"frand\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=urwI7osBXmwC&pg=PA239|title=Listen To Your Messages: And other observations on contemporary Jewish life |first=Yissocher |last=Frand|authorlink=Yissocher Frand|publisher=Mesorah Publications Ltd. |year=1999 |page=239 |isbn=9781578191390}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d34MAQAAMAAJ|journal=Midstream |volume=40 |publisher=Theodor Herzl Foundation |year=1994|page=44|title=Midstream }}</ref> A typical Daf Yomi ''shiur'' lasts one hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chareidi.org/archives5765/PKD65features.htm |title= Jews Around the Globe Celebrate Completion of Shas |author=Yated Ne'eman staff |date=9 March 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=Dei'ah VeDibur}}</ref> Participants study the text together with the commentary of [[Rashi]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uVIwAAAAYAAJ|title=Living with the Sages: Rashi and the Tosafists |first=Dovid |last=Castle |publisher=Feldheim Publishers |year=1996 |volume=1}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Schottenstein Edition of the Babylonian Talmud]], an English-language translation and interpretation published in 73 volumes between 1990 and 2004 by [[ArtScroll]],<ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web |url=http://jewishvoiceny.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=622:artscroll-set-to-release-digital-version-of-schottenstein-talmud&catid=93:art-a-culture&Itemid=276 |title=Artscroll Set to Release Digital Version of Schottenstein Talmud |date=7 March 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Baruch |last=Shubert |work=The Jewish Voice}}</ref> has been credited with significantly increasing the number of English-language participants in the Daf Yomi program.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vqsRAQAAIAAJ |title= The Jewish experience: 2,000 years: A collection of significant events |first=Nachman |last=Zakon |page=262 |publisher=Shaar Press |year=2005 |isbn= 9781578194964}}</ref> The Schottenstein Talmud has also been translated into Hebrew. Additional resources to assist those endeavoring to complete the cycle for the first time are audiotapes, online websites, and [[iPod]]s preloaded with lectures covering every page of the Talmud.<ref name=\"pod\">{{cite web |last=Mindlin |first=Alex |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B03E4DB133CF934A25750C0A9639C8B63 |title=2,000 Talmud Tapes, Or One Loaded IPod |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=17 March 2005 |accessdate=11 October 2007 |quote=Enter the ShasPod. For $399, Mr. Shmidman sends his customers a 20-gigabyte iPod loaded with Talmud lectures given by Rabbi Dovid Grossman of Los Angeles.}}</ref> The Dafyomi Advancement Forum, founded by [[Kollel]] Iyun Hadaf in 1996, is a free resource center offering English-language translations, outlines, charts, analyses and lectures on every ''daf'', as well as answers to any question by email.<ref name=\"kollel\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dafyomi.co.il/ |title=Kollel Iyun Hadaf, Authors of the Dafyomi Advancement Forum |publisher=dafyomi.co.il|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> Meoros HaDaf HaYomi, founded in 1999, disseminates a weekly Daf Yomi study sheet in both Hebrew and English available by email and regular mail. It has recorded ''shiurim'' on the ''daf'' on CD-ROM in English, Hebrew, Yiddish, and French.<ref>{{citation |url=http://jerusalemblueprint.com/events/results.aspx?tid=1 |pages=vii\u2013x |chapter=About Meoros HaDaf HaYomi |title=Meoros HaDaf HaYomi: A discussion of contemporary topics from Maseches Berachos |publisher=Feldheim Publishers |year=2005 |isbn=1-58330-789-3 |access-date=7 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427140341/http://jerusalemblueprint.com/events/results.aspx?tid=1 |archive-date=27 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Siyum HaShas program==\nAs with any siyum, the Siyum HaShas is both an end and a beginning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/m/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=17376 |title=Daf Yomi gathering unites Jews of all stripes |first=Avi |last=Shafran |authorlink=Avi Shafran |work=[[Washington Jewish Week]] |date=13 June 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130408083301/http://washingtonjewishweek.com/m/Articles.aspx?ArticleID=17376 |archivedate=8 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Dozens and even hundreds of [[Gadol|Gedolei Torah]] (Torah leaders) attend each Siyum HaShas. A distinguished [[Rav]] is honored with the recital of the last topic on the last page of Talmud and the saying of the ''[[Hadran (Talmud)|Hadran]]'' (\"We will return\") prayer. The Rav then delivers a scholarly lecture. Another honoree begins the new Daf Yomi cycle with the recital of the first topic on the first page of Talmud. Other rabbis are invited to deliver speeches on the Talmud and on the significance of the event. A special [[Kaddish]], the ''Kaddish Hagadol'', is also said. The program is rounded out with spirited singing and dancing.\n\n===1st Siyum HaShas===\nThe 1st Siyum HaShas took place on 2 February 1931 (15 [[Shevat]] 5691) in several cities in Europe and in [[Jerusalem]], with the main venue being the newly opened Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva in [[Lublin]], Poland. Tens of thousands of Jews attended these events. Rabbi Meir Shapiro presided over the Siyum in his yeshiva in the presence of many leaders of [[History of the Jews in Poland|Polish Jewry]].<ref name=\"daf2\">Shlomi, B. \"The Historic First Siyum HaShas\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 10 May 2012, pp. 12\u201313.</ref> In the United States, Siyums were held in [[Baltimore]] and [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\">Horowitz, Yisroel. \"Celebrating Siyum HaShas in America\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 21 June 2012, p. 3.</ref>\n\n===2nd Siyum HaShas===\nThe 2nd Siyum HaShas was held on 27 June 1938 (28 [[Sivan]] 5698). Again the main venue was the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva, but the founder of that yeshiva and the Daf Yomi program, Rabbi Meir Shapiro, was not present, having died suddenly in 1933 at the age of 46.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vosizneias.com/40348/2009/10/25/new-york-the-76th-yahrzeit-of-rav-meir-shapiro-zatzal-founder-of-the-daf-yomi/ |title=New York \u2013 The 76th Yahrzeit Of Rav Meir Shapiro zatzal Founder of The Daf Yomi |date=25 October 2009 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Yair |last=Hoffman |publisher=[[Vosizneias]]}}</ref> An estimated 15,000<ref name=\"daf3\"/> to 20,000<ref name=\"jta\"/> Jews came from all over Poland to celebrate the milestone together with many Torah luminaries, including the Rebbes of [[Boyan (Hasidic dynasty)|Boyan]]-Cracow, [[Sochatchov (Hasidic dynasty)|Sochatchov]], [[Sadigura (Hasidic dynasty)|Sadigura]], and [[Modzitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Modzhitz]], Rabbi [[Menachem Ziemba]], and Rabbi [[Dov Berish Weidenfeld]]. So many Gedolim were gathered in one place that many [[Halakha|halachic]] queries were sent directly to Lublin. The two-day event culminated with the completion of a [[Sefer Torah]] in memory of Shapiro.<ref name=\"daf3\">Shlomi, B. \"Daf Yomi: A lifeline as the Holocaust looms\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 17 May 2012, pp. 15\u201316.</ref>\n\nIn the United States, Siyums were held in Baltimore, Philadelphia, and [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\nIn [[Mandatory Palestine]], organizers planned to hold a Siyum in the Zikhron Meir neighborhood of [[Bnei Brak]] (named for Rabbi Meir Shapiro). It was cancelled at the last minute by the British mandatory government, which banned all mass gatherings for fear of \"anti-government demonstrations\".<ref name=\"daf3\"/>\n\n===3rd Siyum HaShas===\nThe 3rd Siyum HaShas was held on 19 November 1945 (14 [[Kislev]] 5706), with the main venues in [[Tel Aviv]], [[Haifa]], and Jerusalem. (The Siyum in Tel Aviv, attended by more than 3,000, was delayed one day due to the British-imposed [[curfew]].) Coming as it did after the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], this Siyum was dedicated to the memory of the millions of Jews who had perished.<ref name=try>Shlomi, B. \"Learning Torah in Trying Times\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 24 May 2012, pp. 15\u201316.</ref> A Siyum HaShas was also held in the [[displaced persons camp]] in [[Feldafing]], Germany, by a small group of survivors.<ref name=try/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aish.com/ho/p/48950676.html |title=The Day of My Victory |first=Joseph |last=Friedenson |author-link=Joseph Friedenson|date=27 March 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=[[Aish HaTorah|aish.com]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the Siyum was commemorated in the [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Boro Park]] section of Brooklyn, on [[West Side (Manhattan)|Manhattan's West Side]], and in [[Detroit]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\n===4th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 4th Siyum HaShas on 13 April 1953 (28 [[Nisan]] 5713) also had its main venue in Israel. An estimated 10,000 gathered for the main event in [[Mea Shearim]], following local siyums and speeches by leading rabbis in over half a dozen Jerusalem [[synagogue]]s.<ref name=\"daf4\">Shlomi, B. \"Public Displays of Kiddush Hashem\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 14 June 2012, pp. 20\u201321.</ref><ref name=\"Americanization\">Heilman, Samuel C. [https://books.google.com/books?id=c__ymBsbYdwC&pg=PA311 \"The Ninth Siyum HaShas: A case study in Orthodox contra-acculturation\"] in ''The Americanization of the Jews'', New York University Press, 1995, pp. 315\u2013338. {{ISBN|9780814780015}}</ref> Thousands attended the Siyum HaShas in Tel Aviv and danced afterwards at the central bus station. Well-attended Siyums also took place in Bnei Brak, [[Petah Tikva]], [[Haifa]], and [[Tiberias]].<ref name=\"daf4\"/>\n\nIn New York City, the 4th Siyum HaShas was celebrated at the [[National Council of Young Israel|Young Israel]] of [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]], as well as in [[Bensonhurst, Brooklyn|Bensonhurst]], [[Brownsville, Brooklyn|Brownsville]], [[West Side (Manhattan)|West Side of Manhattan]], and [[the Bronx]].<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\n===5th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 5th Siyum HaShas took place on 5 September 1960 (13 [[Elul]] 5720). In Jerusalem's [[Kikar HaShabbat]], an open-air square at the intersection of the Mea Shearim and [[Geula]] neighborhoods, distinguished Torah leaders addressed the thousands of attendees. In Bnei Brak, police estimated an audience of between 12,000 and 15,000 in an outdoor field. Over 5,000 attended the Siyum in Tel Aviv, where Rabbi [[Yosef Shlomo Kahaneman]], the [[Ponevezh yeshiva|Ponevezher]] Rav, delivered a ''[[Hadran (Talmud)|hadran]]'' that lasted nearly two hours.<ref name=\"daf4\"/>\n\nIn the United States, Rabbi [[Aharon Kotler]] presided over the 5th Siyum HaShas at the Zeirei Agudas Yisroel convention in New York.<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/><ref name=wins>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/prime/ceo-coo-siyum/|title=The CEO, the COO and the Siyum|last=Borchardt|first=Reuvain|date=December 15, 2019|work=Hamodia|accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref> Other Siyums took place in New York City and Baltimore.<ref name=\"Horowitz\"/>\n\n===6th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 6th Siyum HaShas was celebrated in many venues in Israel. The largest gatherings were at Jerusalem's [[International Convention Center (Jerusalem)|International Convention Center]] on 29 January 1968 (28 [[Tevet]] 5728), the Wagschal Hall in Bnei Brak, and the [[Fredric R. Mann Auditorium|Culture Palace]] in Tel Aviv (home of the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]]) on 30 January 1968. At the Tel Aviv event, the choirs of [[Ger (Hasidic dynasty)|Ger]], [[Vizhnitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Vizhnitz]], [[Modzitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Modzhitz]], and [[Chabad]], together with a [[Sephardic Jews|Sephardi]] boys choir and a Haredi Yerushalmi choir, performed between speeches.<ref name=\"daf6\">Shlomi, B. \"The Bnei Yeshiva Protect Us\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 21 June 2012, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\nIn London, the Agudath Israel of Britain organized a Siyum HaShas at the Town Hall in [[Stamford Hill]], attended by groups from [[Manchester]], [[Gateshead]], and [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]], and Agudath Israel leaders from Europe.<ref name=\"daf6\"/>\n\nThe largest Siyum HaShas to date in the United States took place on 28 January 1968<ref name=\"daf6\"/> at the [[Bais Yaakov]] of [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Boro Park]] with 300 people in attendance.<ref name=\"met\">{{cite web |url=http://www.5tjt.com/local-news/13311-metlife-stadium-to-build-a-mechitzah |title=MetLife Stadium To Build A Mechitzah |work=[[Five Towns Jewish Times]] |first=Rabbi Yishai |last=Cooper |date=16 February 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Other Siyums were held in New York City in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]], the Bronx, the West Side of Manhattan, and Bensonhurst; Baltimore; [[Boston]]; [[Chicago]]; and [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"daf6\"/>\n\n===7th Siyum HaShas===\nTens of thousands of participants attended the 7th Siyum HaShas in Jerusalem, which was held on 23 June 1975 (14 [[Tammuz (Hebrew month)|Tammuz]] 5735). The event, which took place in the large courtyard of the Bais Yaakov High School, attracted thousands of religious schoolchildren wearing a special Daf Yomi badge, together with their teachers. Three hundred members of the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] were seated on the huge dais. The central celebration in Tel Aviv, again held at the Culture Palace and again featuring numerous choirs, also drew a huge attendance. In Bnei Brak, more than 10,000 people pressed into the Great Synagogue; the doors and some furnishings buckled under the crush of the crowd. After the ceremony and speeches, the crowd spilled out onto Rabbi Akiva Street for dancing. The Siyum was also marked in [[Netanya]], [[Safed]], [[Ramat Gan]], and, for the first time, in [[Giv'atayim]].<ref name=\"daf7\">Shlomi, B. \"Soldiers Defending Torah\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 28 June 2012, pp. 19\u201320.</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the 7th Siyum HaShas was held on 15 June 1975 at the [[Manhattan Center]] in New York City, drawing an audience of over 5,000.<ref name=\"daf7\"/><ref name=wins/> At this Siyum, the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah|Council of Torah Sages]] of Agudath Israel of America permanently dedicated the Siyum HaShas to the memory of the six million Jews murdered during the Holocaust.<ref name=\"Americanization\"/> Other Siyums took place in Philadelphia and [[Cleveland]]. Around the world, Siyums were held in [[England]], [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]], [[Brazil]], and [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"daf7\"/>\n\n===8th Siyum HaShas===\nThe mid-1970s and early 1980s saw an increase in the [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] population worldwide, fueling the growth of the Daf Yomi program and an increase in locations for the Siyum HaShas beginning with the 8th Siyum.<ref name=\"daf8\"/> At the conclusion of the eighth cycle of Daf Yomi, ''[[The New York Times]]'' estimated that 40,000 individuals worldwide had participated in the seven-and-a-half-year learning cycle.<ref>{{cite web |last=Austin |first=Charles |url=https://select.nytimes.com/search/restricted/article?res=F30B16FD3E5D0C768DDDA80994DA484D81 |title=Thousands Mark Talmudic Milestone |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=15 November 1982 |accessdate=11 October 2007|quote=\"This month marks the end of the study period during which, it is estimated, 40,000 Orthodox Jews around the world clustered around the ancient commentaries on the Scriptures\".}}</ref> According to Agudath Israel, close to 250,000 people worldwide participated in the 8th Siyum HaShas.<ref name=\"daf8\">Shlomi, B. \"For the Glory of Chareidi Jewry\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 5 July 2012, pp. 13\u201314.</ref> The largest attendance was in Israel, with 10,000 attendees at the [[Menora Mivtachim Arena|Yad Eliyahu Arena]] in Tel Aviv on 21 November 1982 (5 [[Kislev]] 5743), 10,000 at Jerusalem's International Convention Center, thousands in Bnei Brak at Wagschal Hall, and hundreds in Haifa, Petah Tikva, and, for the first time, in [[Ashdod]]. At the Jerusalem event, a special certificate was awarded to four men who had completed all eight cycles of Daf Yomi.<ref name=\"daf8\"/>\n\nThe main Siyum HaShas in the United States was celebrated on 14 November 1982 at the [[Felt Forum]] in New York City, with over 5,000 participants.<ref name=\"klass\"/><ref name=\"Americanization\"/> This program was broadcast to gatherings in Chicago, Los Angeles, [[Toronto]], and Montreal. Other Siyums took place in Detroit; Cleveland; and [[Monsey, New York]].<ref name=\"daf8\"/>\n\n===9th Siyum HaShas===\n[[File:Madison Square Garden Transformation Stage 1.jpg|right|thumb|[[Madison Square Garden]], site of the 9th, 10th, and 11th Siyum HaShas in New York.]]\nAt the Agudath Israel of America convention following the 8th Siyum HaShas in New York, Agudah chairman Rabbi [[Moshe Sherer]] announced that he wished to book [[Madison Square Garden]] for the next Siyum HaShas, to be held on 26 April 1990. Many were skeptical that the stadium, seating 20,000, could be filled, considering that the 8th Siyum HaShas in New York had attracted only 5,000. But Agudath Israel of America went ahead and paid a nonrefundable deposit two and a half years in advance of the Siyum, and attendance met all expectations, with over 20,000 in attendance.<ref name=\"klass\"/><ref name=\"met\"/><ref name=\"daf9\"/> Tickets on the main floor, priced at $100 apiece, were sold out for weeks in advance, and the women's section was also sold out.<ref name=\"Americanization\"/> Other Siyums were held in Baltimore, Chicago, Cleveland, Los Angeles, Toronto, Montreal, and Tel Aviv.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qOgCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA15 ''[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]''], 17 February 1997, pp. 15\u201316.</ref>\n\nEnormous crowds were seen at the 9th Siyum HaShas in Israel's main cities on 24 April 1990 (29 Nisan 5750). These included a Siyum in Tel Aviv at the [[Menora Mivtachim Arena|Yad Eliyahu Arena]], a Siyum in Jerusalem in the spacious Bais Yaakov High School courtyard, and a Siyum in Bnei Brak. Special children's Siyums were also held in Jerusalem (with students from 84 [[Talmud Torah]]s and schools in attendance) and in Bnei Brak (with 5,000 children together with leading rabbis and educators in attendance).<ref name=\"daf9\">Shlomi, B. \"An Extraordinary Kiddush Hashem\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 12 July 2012, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\nThe 9th Siyum HaShas in [[London]] drew a large audience and lasted six hours, followed by a festive meal. Smaller events took place in Manchester, Gateshead, and among local Daf Yomi groups in England. In [[Melbourne]], Australia, home to eight regular Daf Yomi ''shiurim'', the central Siyum HaShas drew 1,000 people.<ref name=\"daf9\"/>\n\n===10th Siyum HaShas===\nThe 10th Siyum HaShas in the United States took place on 28 September 1997 at two New York City locations: [[Madison Square Garden]], with an audience of 25,000, and the [[Nassau Coliseum]], with an audience of 20,000.<ref name=\"klass\"/> Siyums were also held in [[Boston]], Cleveland, [[Chicago]], Los Angeles, [[Pittsburgh]], and [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]],<ref name=\"daf10\"/> bringing total U.S. participation to 70,000 individuals.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zjfPA1NZFbgC&pg=PR19 |page=xix |title=The World of the Yeshiva: An intimate portrait of Orthodox Jewry |first=William B. |last=Helmreich |year=2000 |publisher=KTAV Publishing House |isbn= 9780881256413}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IEoMEW8Xy5wC&pg=PA9510|title= Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the 105th Congress Second Session|volume=144 \u2013 Part 7 |publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]] |year=1998 |page=9510}}</ref> Siyums also took place in Toronto, Ontario and Montreal, Quebec in Canada, and Melbourne, Australia.<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nIn Israel, the central Siyum HaShas was held at Tel Aviv's Yad Eliyahu Arena on 28 September 1997 (26 [[Elul]] 5757) with thousands in attendance, and was broadcast live to other locations. The honor of starting the new cycle of Daf Yomi went to Rabbi [[Shmuel Wosner]], a student of Rabbi Meir Shapiro, who shared his memories of the first Siyum HaShas in 1931. The [[Shabbat]] preceding this Siyum was billed as \"Shabbos Daf Yomi\", with rabbis calling on Israelis to increase their study of Daf Yomi. Other Siyums were held in [[Beth midrash|battei medrash]] (study halls) in Jerusalem and Bnei Brak, and in Ramat [[Vizhnitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Vizhnitz]] in Haifa.<ref name=\"daf10\">Shlomi, B. \"Holy Torah, Plead for Us\". ''Hamodia'' Magazine, 2 August 2012, pp. 12\u201322.</ref>\n\nIn England, the central Siyum HaShas was held in the Sobel Center in London, drawing thousands of attendees. Over 2,500 attended the ''[[seudat mitzvah]]'' (celebratory meal) hosted by Agudath Israel in London. Another thousand attended Siyums in Manchester and Gateshead.<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\n===11th Siyum HaShas===\nAn estimated 300,000 people worldwide participated in the 11th Siyum HaShas.<ref name=\"jta\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/12522/Celebrationofdaily |title=Daf Yomi program has Polish roots |first=Carolyn |last=Slutsky |date=30 November 1999 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415041722/http://www.jta.org/news/article/1999/11/30/12522/Celebrationofdaily |archivedate=15 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The largest celebrations were held on 1 March 2005 in three locations in the New York area: Madison Square Garden, the [[Continental Airlines Arena]] in [[New Jersey]], and the [[Jacob K. Javits Convention Center]], with a combined 45,000 attendees.<ref name=\"klass\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Newman |first=Andy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/02/nyregion/02talmud.html |title=Orthodox Jews Celebrate End of a True Sabbatical |work=The New York Times |date=2 March 2005 |accessdate=11 October 2007}}</ref> Portions of each program were telecast to the other sites and to more than 50 locations countrywide,<ref name=\"daf10\"/> including the [[Rosemont Theatre]] in Chicago, the [[Walt Disney Concert Hall]] in Los Angeles, and the [[Ricoh Coliseum]] in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.torah.org/features/spirfocus/siyumhashas.html# |title=The Secret of the Jews |first=Rabbi Avi |last=Shafran |authorlink=Avi Shafran |year=2005 |publisher=torah.org |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050310014240/http://www.torah.org/features/spirfocus/siyumhashas.html |archivedate=10 March 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The programs were also broadcast to 20 overseas locations.<ref name=\"daf10\"/> The honor of reciting the final portion of the final page at the Continental Arena event was given to Rabbi Chaim Stein, [[rosh yeshiva]] of the [[Telshe yeshiva]] of [[Wickliffe, Ohio]], who was making his ninth personal Siyum HaShas<ref name=\"daf10\"/> and had participated in each of the ten preceding events, including the first one held at the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva in 1931.<ref>{{cite web |last=Goldfeder |first=Moshe |url=http://media.www.yucommentator.com/media/storage/paper652/news/2005/03/08/News/Eleventh.Siyum.Hashas.Hosts.Record.Breaking.Turnout-885612.shtml |title=Eleventh Siyum Hashas Hosts Record Breaking Turnout |work=The Commentator |publisher=[[Yeshiva University]] |date=8 March 2005 |accessdate=11 October 2007 |quote=\"The climax of the evening, the actual completion of the Talmud achieved by the reading of the last line, was performed in New Jersey by Rabbi Chaim Stein, head of the Telshe Yeshiva of Wickliffe. Rabbi Stein has the distinction of having participated in every Siyum HaShas since the very first, way back in Poland, 1931\". |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070701223222/http://media.www.yucommentator.com/media/storage/paper652/news/2005/03/08/News/Eleventh.Siyum.Hashas.Hosts.Record.Breaking.Turnout-885612.shtml |archivedate=1 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Israel, 10,000 tickets prepared for the central Siyum HaShas at Yad Eliyahu Arena in Tel Aviv on 1 March 2005 (20 [[Adar]] I, 5765) sold out immediately. The proceedings were viewed by live satellite hookup in Jerusalem, Bnei Brak, and Ashdod. Siyums were also held in Jerusalem at the International Convention Center, in the [[Zikhron Moshe]] synagogue, in the [[Pinsk-Karlin (Hasidic dynasty)|Pinsk-Karlin]] ''beis medrash'', in [[Kiryat Belz]], and at the [[Erlau (Hasidic dynasty)|Erlau]] yeshiva. An English-language Siyum at the Jerusalem Convention Center was attended by the Rebbes of [[Boyan (Hasidic dynasty)|Boyan]], [[Karlin-Stolin (Hasidic dynasty)|Karlin-Stolin]], [[Kaliv (Hasidic dynasty)|Kaliv]], and [[Pittsburg (Hasidic dynasty)|Pittsburg]], as well as by English-speaking roshei yeshiva Rabbi [[Nosson Tzvi Finkel (Mir)|Nosson Tzvi Finkel]], Rabbi [[Chaim Pinchas Scheinberg]], Rabbi Yitzchak Sheiner, and Rabbi [[Mendel Weinbach]]. Other Siyums were held in Bnei Brak, Haifa, Ashdod, Netanya, Petah Tikva, [[Rehovot]], [[Kokhav Ya'akov|Tel Zion]], and [[Kiryat Ata]].<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nThe 11th Siyum HaShas was also celebrated by 4,000 people in London,<ref name=\"daf10\"/> 2,000 people in Manchester,<ref name=\"daf10\"/> and at events in [[Antwerp]],<ref name=\"daf10\"/> and Melbourne and Sydney, Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chareidi.org/archives5765/vayakhel/aaustrlvyk65.htm |title=Gala Siyum HaShas in Melbourne Australia |date=2 March 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |publisher=Dei'ah VeDibur |author=Yated Ne'eman Australian correspondent}}</ref> The scope of celebrations marking the 11th Siyum HaShas was described in one newspaper account as follows:\n<blockquote>Among the [U.S.] cities where Siyums were held were [[Atlanta]], Baltimore, Boston, [[Dallas]], [[Detroit]], [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]], [[Denver]], [[Houston]], Los Angeles, [[Lakewood, New Jersey|Lakewood]], [[Miami]], [[Milwaukee]], [[New Orleans]], [[St. Louis]], [[Seattle]], [[Cincinnati]], [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, Cleveland, and Chicago.</blockquote>\n<blockquote>Siyums were also held in [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada; [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina; [[Caracas]], Venezuela; [[Sao Paulo]], Brazil; [[Santiago]], Chile; [[Johannesburg]], South Africa; [[Lublin]], Poland, [[Moscow]], [[Saint Petersburg|St. Petersburg]], [[Kiev]], and [[Odessa]] in the [[Former Soviet Union]]; [[Hong Kong]], China; and [[Sydney]], Australia.<ref name=\"daf10\"/></blockquote>\n\nComing as it did the day before the [[Bereavement in Judaism#Yahrtzeit, Nahala|yahrzeit]] of Hasidic master Reb [[Elimelech of Lizensk]], when hundreds traditionally make a pilgrimage to his grave in [[Le\u017cajsk]], Poland, two Siyums were celebrated in Poland, including the first at the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva since 1931 (see below). A large group from Israel traveled to the former ''beis medrash'' of the Gerrer Rebbes in [[G\u00f3ra Kalwaria]]. A Siyum HaShas was made in [[Moscow]] by the united Jewish communities in Russia under the leadership of Chief Rabbi [[Berel Lazar]].<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nThe 11th Siyum HaShas was also marked by an event for non-[[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] Jews called Jewish Unity Live 2005. The central venue, the [[New Jersey Performing Arts Center]], featured [[Elie Wiesel]], U.S. Senator [[Joe Lieberman|Joseph Lieberman]], and other celebrities; gatherings were also held on college campuses and military bases across the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/features/same_page  |title=On the Same Page |date=25 February 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Steve |last=Lipman |work=[[The Jewish Week]]}}</ref>\n\n===12th Siyum HaShas===\n[[File:New Meadowlands Stadium Mezz Corner.jpg|right|thumb|[[MetLife Stadium]], site of the 12th and 13th Siyum HaShas]]\nThe [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], which has seating for 82,500, was the main U.S. venue for the 12th Siyum HaShas on 1 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/General+News/135894/BREAKING-NEWS%3A-Siyum-HaShas-WILL-Take-Place-In-MetLife-Stadium-Despite-Weather-Reports-%5BUPDATED-INFO%5D.html |title=BREAKING NEWS: Siyum HaShas WILL Take Place In MetLife Stadium Despite Weather Reports|date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=2 August 2012 |work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref> An additional 8,500 folding chairs were placed on the playing field, and a dais of approximately 500 seats accommodated [[Admor]]im, [[rosh yeshiva|roshei yeshiva]], and distinguished rabbis. An additional section of 1,000 seats was reserved for teachers of Daf Yomi ''shiurim''.<ref name=\"nj\">{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-news/nearly-100-000-jews-to-gather-in-n-j-to-celebrate-completion-of-talmud-cycle.premium-1.454493 |title=Nearly 100,000 Jews to gather in N.J. to celebrate completion of Talmud cycle |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=1 August 2012 |first=Debra |last=Nussbaum Cohen |work=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref><ref name=\"july\">{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/will-rav-shteinman-be-attending-the-siyum-hashas-at-metlife-stadium |title=Will Rav Shteinman Be Attending the Siyum Hashas at MetLife Stadium? |first=Casriel |last=Bauman |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=22 July 2012 |publisher=matzav.com}}</ref> All 92,000 seats were sold out.<ref name=\"sold\">{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/all-93000-tickets-sold-siyum-hashas-to-be-largest-event-ever-at-metlife-stadium |title=All 93,000 Tickets Sold: Siyum Hashas to Be Largest Event Ever at MetLife Stadium |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2012 |publisher=matzav.com |first=Casriel |last=Bauman}}</ref> A total of 2,200 [[Plasma display|plasma screens]] were set up inside the stadium and four [[Jumbotron]] screens were positioned outside the stadium for overflow attendees. Female attendees, who constituted an estimated 20 percent of the crowd, were seated in the upper deck of the stadium behind a {{convert|12|ft|adj=on}} high, {{convert|2.5|mi|adj=on}} long ''[[mechitza]]'' (curtain divider) that was drawn during prayers.<ref name=\"nj\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hwIi1pRFQMRR-ROz7eCSJ-eKPn9g?docId=aa385adeba904f3a991a17bf0c8d037f |title=NJ's MetLife Stadium site of Talmud celebration |first=Kate |last=Zezima |date=1 August 2012 |accessdate=1 August 2012 |publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Satellite broadcasts and web feeds were piped to over 100 locations, including those in Chicago, Baltimore, Toronto, Montreal, Los Angeles, Mexico City, Uruguay, Buenos Aires, Argentina, Melbourne, Hong Kong, and Lublin, Poland.<ref name=\"sold\"/>\n\nFor the first time, a [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] Siyum HaShas was also held, on 6 August 2012, at [[Congregation Shearith Israel]] on Manhattan's [[Upper West Side]].<ref name=\"nj\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/2012/06/27/3099366/ny-modern-orthodox-institutions-to-celebrate-siyum-hashas |title=N.Y. Modern Orthodox institutions to celebrate Siyum HaShas |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701071529/http://www.jta.org/news/article/2012/06/27/3099366/ny-modern-orthodox-institutions-to-celebrate-siyum-hashas |archivedate=1 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://matzav.com/controversial-chovevei-torah-rosh-yeshiva-rabbi-linzer-to-address-modern-orthodox-siyum-hashas-also-featuring-female-mesaymim |first=Casriel |last=Bauman |publisher=matzav.com |title=Controversial Chovevei Torah Rosh Yeshiva Rabbi Linzer to Address 'Modern Orthodox' Siyum Hashas Also Featuring Female Mesaymim |date=5 July 2012 |accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> This event featured lectures on various aspects of both the Jerusalem and the Babylonian Talmud, and participation by female Torah scholars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.siyumhashas12.com |title=NYC Modern Orthodox Siyum HaShas website |first=Dov |last=Weinstock |date=17 July 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120708230422/http://siyumhashas12.com/ |archivedate=8 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTens of thousands attended Siyums in Israel. These included the [[Dirshu]] World Siyum at the [[Menora Mivtachim Arena|Yad Eliyahu Arena]] in Tel Aviv, the National Siyum HaShas in [[Petah Tikva]], a Siyum organized by Agudath Israel and [[Degel HaTorah]] in the [[French Hill]] neighborhood of Jerusalem, and a Siyum organized by the [[Shas]] political party at [[Teddy Stadium]] in Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.5tjt.com/international-news/14315-dirshu-world-siyum-48-hours-of-achdus-simcha-and-accomplishment |title=Dirshu World Siyum: 48 hours of achdus, simcha, and accomplishment |work=[[Five Towns Jewish Times]] |first=Yonoson |last=Klein |date=24 May 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/157387 |title=Preparations Underway for Siyum HaShas in Tel Aviv |date=1 July 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |first=Hana Levi |last=Julian |work=[[Arutz Sheva|Israel National News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theyeshivaworld.com/article.php?p=130807 |title=Jerusalem City Hall Says 'NO' to Funding Siyum HaShas for Shas |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[Yeshiva World News]]}}</ref> There were two English-language Siyums at [[International Convention Center (Jerusalem)|Jerusalem's International Convention Center]], one sponsored by Dirshu on 31 July<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/157553 |title=Final Preparations for Dirshu's English Siyum HaShas |first=Gil |last=Ronen |work=[[Arutz Sheva]] |date=5 July 2012 |accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref> and one organized by Kollel Iyun Hadaf on 5 August.<ref name=\"kollel\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishpress.com/news/israel/behind-the-plans-for-jerusalem-siyum-hashas-celebration/2012/01/11/ |title=Behind The Plans For Jerusalem Siyum Hashas Celebration |first=Steve K. |last=Walz |date=11 January 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |work=[[The Jewish Press]]}}</ref> The various Religious Zionist organizations sponsored a separate siyum at the same Convention Center on 2 August, and there was another English language siyum at Jerusalem's Great Synagogue on 9 August.\n\nA new edition of the Talmud was launched to coincide with the 12th Siyum HaShas by [[Koren Publishers]]. Known as the Koren Talmud Bavli, this edition features translation and commentary by Rabbi [[Adin Steinsaltz]]. The project, slated to be 42 volumes, is overseen by Rabbi Dr. [[Tzvi Hersh Weinreb]] who serves as editor-in-chief.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jta.org/2012/09/10/life-religion/siyum-hashas-inspiring-newcomers-to-daily-talmud-study|title=Siyum HaShas inspiring newcomers to daily Talmud study |work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |first=Neil |last=Rubin |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===13th Siyum HaShas===\n[[File:13th Siyum HaShas 2019.jpg|thumb|13th Siyum HaShas in MetLife Stadium.]]\n[[File:Dirshu Siyum Hashas NY 2020.jpg|thumb|[[Dirshu]] Siyum HaShas on February 9, 2020, in the [[Prudential Center]], [[Newark, New Jersey]]]]\nFor the 13th Siyum HaShas, whose study cycle concluded on the 7th of [[Tevet]] 5780 (January 4, 2020), celebrations were scheduled to take place in locations in the U.S., Europe, Israel, and other countries, in January and February 2020. The main event in the United States, staged by [[Agudath Israel of America]], took place on January 1 at [[MetLife Stadium]], which has capacity for 92,000 seats, with a second location at [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn, NY]].<ref name=wins/> Concerned about holding an outdoor event during the [[New Jersey]] winter, planners had proposed holding the main siyum in five different indoor venues in New York, New Jersey, and Philadelphia simultaneously with [[live streaming]] hook-ups between them.<ref name=wins/> But the [[Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah#In the United States|Moetzes Gedolei HaTorah]] of Agudath Israel of America opted to hold the siyum in one place based on the principle of ''[[b'rov am hadrat melech]]'', that God's honor is increased when a large number of Jews gather in the same place.<ref name=wins/>\n\nEarly Siyum HaShas celebrations also took place in December 2019 in [[Melbourne]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/2019/12/17/melbourne-holds-siyum-hashas/|title=Melbourne Holds Siyum HaShas|date=December 17, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019|work=Hamodia}}</ref> and [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/2019/12/23/siyum-hashas-held-vienna-austria/|title=Siyum HaShas Held in Vienna, Austria|first=Rivka|last=Junger|date=December 23, 2019|accessdate=December 23, 2019|work=Hamodia}}</ref>\n\nIn Israel, the Hadran organization organized a Siyum HaShas celebration focussing on women's learning and teaching of Talmud in general and the Daf Yomi in particular.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/life/437804/thousands-gather-to-celebrate-womens-talmud-study-in-jerusalem/|title=Thousands gather to celebrate women\u2019s Talmud study in Jerusalem|last=Blumberg|first=Ilana|date=January 6, 2020|website=The Forward|publisher=The Jewish Forward|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n[[Dirshu]] held their own Siyum in the [[Prudential Center]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]] on February 9, 2020.\n\n==Return to Lublin==\nWith the closure of the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva by the Nazis and the conversion of the yeshiva to a medical academy, the Siyum HaShas was not held in its original venue for many cycles. In 1998 the yeshiva was returned to the Jewish community of [[Warsaw]], which undertook renovations.<ref name=\"jta\"/> In March 2005, Rabbi David Singer, an Orthodox Jew from [[Brooklyn]], New York, whose father, Rabbi Joseph Singer, the [[Pilzno (Hasidic dynasty)#Rabbi Joseph Singer|Pilzno]] Rav, had been born in Poland,<ref>Friedman, C. \"The Grave of the Koloshitzer Rav, Hy\"d\". ''[[Hamodia]]'' Features, 22 November 2012, p. C2</ref> organized the 11th Siyum HaShas in the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva.<ref name=\"jta\"/><ref name=ami>Krausz, Yossi. \"Time Traveler\". ''Ami'', 13 June 2012, pp. 54\u201363.</ref> Chaired by Rabbi [[Baruch Taub]], rabbi emeritus of [[Beth Avraham Yoseph of Toronto]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ou.org/torah/author/Rabbi_Baruch_Taub |title=Rabbi Baruch Taub |publisher=[[Orthodox Union]] |year=2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528171719/http://www.ou.org/torah/author/Rabbi_Baruch_Taub |archivedate=28 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the event was linked by satellite to the one in New York and was attended by over 200 participants,<ref name=\"jta\"/> including the Rebbes of [[Sadigura (Hasidic dynasty)|Sadigura]], [[Modzitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Modzhitz]], [[Nadvorna (Hasidic dynasty)|Nadvorna]], and [[Biala (Hasidic dynasty)|Biala]]; Rabbi [[Yona Metzger]], [[Chief Rabbinate of Israel|Chief Rabbi of Israel]], and Israeli politician Rabbi [[Menachem Porush]].<ref name=\"daf10\"/>\n\nSinger organized the 12th Siyum HaShas at the Chachmei Lublin Yeshiva on 1 August 2012. Participants viewed a simultaneous broadcast from the event taking place that same day at the [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[New Jersey]].<ref name=\"nesivos\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nesivos.com/index.php/siyum-hashas-lublin-2/ |title=Siyum HaShas Lublin & Poland Tour |publisher=nesivos.com |year=2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625103239/http://www.nesivos.com/index.php/siyum-hashas-lublin-2 |archivedate=25 June 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Other uses==\n''Siyum HaShas'' also refers to any individual's or group's [[Siyum|completion]] of all 2,711 [[List of masechtot, chapters, mishnahs and pages in the Talmud|pages of Talmud]]. Many rabbis and Torah scholars have completed the study of the entire Talmud one or more times in their lifetimes.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dEoW-Q_Wq2AC&pg=PA186  |title=The Maggid Speaks: Favorite Stories and Parables of Rabbi Sholom Schwadron, Shlita, Maggid of Jerusalem |last1=Krohn |first1=Paysach J. |authorlink1=Paysach Krohn |last2=Schwadron |first2=Shalom |authorlink2=Shalom Schwadron |publisher=Mesorah Publications Ltd. |year=1987 |isbn= 9780899062303|page=186}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=-Jb4w78HMzUC&pg=PA445 |title=The Legacy of Maran Rav Aharon Kotler: A vivid portrait of the teachings, qualities, and accomplishments of the venerable rosh hayeshiva |page=445 |first=Yitzchok |last=Dershowitz |publisher=[[Feldheim Publishers]] |isbn= 9781583308752|year=2005}}</ref> Synagogues, organizations, and community groups also complete the Talmud on a yearly basis, marking an annual Siyum HaShas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/4564767/jewish/What-Is-a-Siyum-Hashas.htm|title=What Is a Siyum HaShas?|work=[[Chabad|Chabad.org]]|year=2019|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.5tjt.com/inwood-celebrates-second-annual-siyum-hashas\n|title=Inwood Celebrates Second Annual Siyum HaShas|work=Five Towns Jewish Times |date=29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n|title=Leadership And A Vision For The Future: RAA's 29th Annual Siyum HaShas\n|url=http://www.5tjt.com/leadership-vision-future-raas-29th-annual-siyum-hashas|work=Five Towns Jewish Times| date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref> An initiative known as a Shas-A-Thon brings hundreds and even thousands of participants together to study and complete the entire Talmud in one day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hamodia.com/2018/12/31/entire-shas-finished-one-day-yerushalayim/|title=Entire Shas Finished on One Day in Yerushalayim|date=December 31, 2018|accessdate=December 25, 2019|work=Hamodia}}</ref> This initiative is sometimes used as a fund-raiser, with participants collecting pledges from donors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://shasathon.org/5780/index.html|title=Bringing Hope Through Torah|publisher=ATIME Shas-A-Thon|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of masechtot, chapters, mishnahs and pages in the Talmud]]\n* [[Talmud]]\n* [[Agudath Israel of America]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commonscat|Siyum HaShas}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thesiyum.org The Siyum Official website]\n*[https://vimeo.com/65770304 Video Highlights of 12th Siyum HaShas in MetLife Stadium]\n*[http://www.vosizneias.com/111068/2012/08/01/east-rutherford-nj-photos-throughout-evening-of-whats-happening Photos of the 12th Siyum HaShas in MetLife Stadium]\n*[http://www.chareidi.org/archives5765/PKD65features.htm \"Jews Around the Globe Celebrate Completion of Shas\"] Overview of events celebrating the 11th Siyum HaShas\n*[https://shiur.com/category.php?cat=siyum-hashas Collection of Siyum HaShas Videos over the years] \n \n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States|Communal activities}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siyum HaShas}}\n[[Category:Talmud]]\n[[Category:1923 establishments in Poland]]\n[[he:\u05d4\u05d3\u05e3 \u05d4\u05d9\u05d5\u05de\u05d9]]\n", "name_user": "SamsonKriger", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added clarification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siyum_HaShas"}
{"title_page": "F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Sarriugarte|Montoya}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| fullname = F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte Montoya\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|11|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Durango, Biscay|Durango]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.74}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Queen City Mutiny]] (Technical Director)\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1981\u20131982 | youthclubs1 = [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|Athletic Bilbao]]\n| years1 = 1982\u20131986 | clubs1 = [[Bilbao Athletic]] | caps1 = 99 | goals1 = 29\n| years2 = 1984\u20131989 | clubs2 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] | caps2 = 68 | goals2 = 13\n| years3 = 1989\u20131994 | clubs3 = [[Real Oviedo|Oviedo]] | caps3 = 91 | goals3 = 15\n| years4 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs4 = [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]] | caps4 = 27 | goals4 = 11\n| years5 = 1995 | clubs5 = [[Barakaldo CF|Barakaldo]] | caps5 = 5 | goals5 = 2\n| years6 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs6 = [[UDA Gramenet|Gramenet]] | caps6 = 11 | goals6 = 3\n| totalcaps = 301 | totalgoals = 73\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =\n| manageryears1 = 2000\u20132003 | managerclubs1 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2003\u20132004 | managerclubs2 = [[CD Basconia|Basconia]]\n| manageryears3 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs3 = [[Bilbao Athletic]]\n| manageryears4 = 2006 | managerclubs4 = [[Athletic Bilbao]]\n| manageryears5 = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs5 = [[CD Varea|Varea]]\n| manageryears6 = 2009 | managerclubs6 = [[CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]]\n| manageryears7= 2011\u20132012 | managerclubs7 = [[Sestao River Club|Sestao]]\n| manageryears8 = 2012\u20132013 | managerclubs8 = [[Real Oviedo|Oviedo]]\n| manageryears9 = 2015 | managerclubs9 = [[Sestao River Club|Sestao]]\n| manageryears10 = 2019\u2013 | managerclubs10 = [[Charlotte Independence]] (assistant)\n| club-update =\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte Montoya''' (born 6 November 1964) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], and an [[Manager (association football)|assistant coach]] for American club [[Charlotte Independence]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Durango, Biscay]], Sarriugarte represented [[Athletic Bilbao]] for five seasons \u2013 having arrived at the club at age 16 \u2013 but only started featuring regularly for the first team in [[1986\u201387 La Liga|1986\u201387]], after appearing in 99 games for [[Bilbao Athletic|the reserves]] and scoring 29 goals. He then spent another five years in [[La Liga]] with [[Asturias]]' [[Real Oviedo]], where he was also never relegated (but played only three matches in his last two seasons combined).\n\nSarriugarte retired in 1996 at the age of 31 after playing [[1994\u201395 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|one season]] with [[UD Las Palmas]] and splitting [[1995\u201396 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his last year]] with local [[Barakaldo CF]] and [[UDA Gramenet]], with all the sides competing in the lower leagues. In the top flight, he amassed totals of 159 matches and 28 goals; his debut in the latter competition came on 9 September 1984 in a 0\u20133 away loss against [[Sevilla FC]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1984/09/10/pagina-12/1435705/pdf.html|title=3\u20130: El Sevilla encontr\u00f3 un ariete|trans-title=3\u20130: Sevilla found a battering ram|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=R.|last=R\u00edos|language=es|date=10 September 1984|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> due to a [[Strike action|strike]] from the professional footballers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elnortedecastilla.es/20110330/deportes/mas-futbol/liga-panales-1984-20110330.html|title=La Liga en pa\u00f1ales de 1984|trans-title=League wearing diapers in 1984|newspaper=[[El Norte de Castilla]]|first=Santiago|last=Hidalgo Chacel|language=es|date=30 March 2011|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nSarriugarte took up coaching in the early 2000s, with the [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|various sides]] of his first club Athletic. On 8 July 2006, following the dismissal of [[Javier Clemente]], he was appointed first-team manager by president [[Fernando Lamikiz]]; just four months later, however, he was relieved of his duties after a 1\u20133 home defeat against [[Sevilla FC]] which saw them drop into the 18th position,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=394070&type=story&cc=null|title=Athletico Bilbao appoint Esnal as new coach|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=29 November 2006|access-date=24 March 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024131147/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=394070&type=story&cc=null|archive-date=24 October 2012|df=}}</ref> and eventually again [[2006\u201307 La Liga|barely avoiding relegation]].\n\nIn June 2009, Sarriugarte signed at [[CD Varea]] (soon to be named [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]]), [[2008\u201309 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|freshly promoted]] to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], but stepped down before [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the campaign]] began.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elcorreo.com/alava/20090621/deportes/la-rioja/varea-descarta-felix-sarriugarte-20090621.html|title=El Varea descarta a F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte como t\u00e9cnico|trans-title=Varea release F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte as coach|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|language=es|date=21 June 2009|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> On 16 July 2012, after having led [[Sestao River Club]] to [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|safety in that level]], he joined another team in the same tier, Oviedo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2012/07/16/futbol/mas_futbol/1342451197.html|title=Sarriugarte ser\u00e1 el nuevo entrenador del Oviedo|trans-title=Sarriugarte to be new Oviedo coach|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=F.|last=Fern\u00e1ndez|language=es|date=16 July 2012|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Charlotte Independence]] announced on 17 January 2019 that Sarriugarte had joined the technical staff of the club as an assistant manager, under [[Jim McGuinness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charlotteindependence.com/news_article/show/986034|title=McGuinness appoints former La Liga manager to assistant coach|publisher=Charlotte Independence|first=James|last=Thomas|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|746}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|746}}\n*{{Athletic Bilbao profile|id=8/sarriugarte}}\n\n{{Charlotte Independence squad}}\n{{Bilbao Athletic managers}}\n{{Athletic Bilbao managers}}\n{{Real Oviedo managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarriugarte, Felix}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Durango, Biscay]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Bilbao Athletic footballers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo players]]\n[[Category:UD Las Palmas players]]\n[[Category:Barakaldo CF footballers]]\n[[Category:UDA Gramenet footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao B managers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao managers]]\n[[Category:Sestao River managers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo managers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Sarriugarte|Montoya}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| fullname = F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte Montoya\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1964|11|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Durango, Biscay|Durango]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.74}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Charlotte Independence]] (assistant)\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1981\u20131982 | youthclubs1 = [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|Athletic Bilbao]]\n| years1 = 1982\u20131986 | clubs1 = [[Bilbao Athletic]] | caps1 = 99 | goals1 = 29\n| years2 = 1984\u20131989 | clubs2 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] | caps2 = 68 | goals2 = 13\n| years3 = 1989\u20131994 | clubs3 = [[Real Oviedo|Oviedo]] | caps3 = 91 | goals3 = 15\n| years4 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs4 = [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]] | caps4 = 27 | goals4 = 11\n| years5 = 1995 | clubs5 = [[Barakaldo CF|Barakaldo]] | caps5 = 5 | goals5 = 2\n| years6 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs6 = [[UDA Gramenet|Gramenet]] | caps6 = 11 | goals6 = 3\n| totalcaps = 301 | totalgoals = 73\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =\n| manageryears1 = 2000\u20132003 | managerclubs1 = [[Athletic Bilbao]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2003\u20132004 | managerclubs2 = [[CD Basconia|Basconia]]\n| manageryears3 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs3 = [[Bilbao Athletic]]\n| manageryears4 = 2006 | managerclubs4 = [[Athletic Bilbao]]\n| manageryears5 = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs5 = [[CD Varea|Varea]]\n| manageryears6 = 2009 | managerclubs6 = [[CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]]\n| manageryears7= 2011\u20132012 | managerclubs7 = [[Sestao River Club|Sestao]]\n| manageryears8 = 2012\u20132013 | managerclubs8 = [[Real Oviedo|Oviedo]]\n| manageryears9 = 2015 | managerclubs9 = [[Sestao River Club|Sestao]]\n| manageryears10 = 2019\u2013 | managerclubs10 = [[Charlotte Independence]] (assistant)\n| club-update =\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte Montoya''' (born 6 November 1964) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], and an [[Manager (association football)|assistant coach]] for American club [[Charlotte Independence]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Durango, Biscay]], Sarriugarte represented [[Athletic Bilbao]] for five seasons \u2013 having arrived at the club at age 16 \u2013 but only started featuring regularly for the first team in [[1986\u201387 La Liga|1986\u201387]], after appearing in 99 games for [[Bilbao Athletic|the reserves]] and scoring 29 goals. He then spent another five years in [[La Liga]] with [[Asturias]]' [[Real Oviedo]], where he was also never relegated (but played only three matches in his last two seasons combined).\n\nSarriugarte retired in 1996 at the age of 31 after playing [[1994\u201395 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|one season]] with [[UD Las Palmas]] and splitting [[1995\u201396 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his last year]] with local [[Barakaldo CF]] and [[UDA Gramenet]], with all the sides competing in the lower leagues. In the top flight, he amassed totals of 159 matches and 28 goals; his debut in the latter competition came on 9 September 1984 in a 0\u20133 away loss against [[Sevilla FC]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1984/09/10/pagina-12/1435705/pdf.html|title=3\u20130: El Sevilla encontr\u00f3 un ariete|trans-title=3\u20130: Sevilla found a battering ram|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=R.|last=R\u00edos|language=es|date=10 September 1984|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> due to a [[Strike action|strike]] from the professional footballers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elnortedecastilla.es/20110330/deportes/mas-futbol/liga-panales-1984-20110330.html|title=La Liga en pa\u00f1ales de 1984|trans-title=League wearing diapers in 1984|newspaper=[[El Norte de Castilla]]|first=Santiago|last=Hidalgo Chacel|language=es|date=30 March 2011|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nSarriugarte took up coaching in the early 2000s, with the [[Athletic Bilbao cantera|various sides]] of his first club Athletic. On 8 July 2006, following the dismissal of [[Javier Clemente]], he was appointed first-team manager by president [[Fernando Lamikiz]]; just four months later, however, he was relieved of his duties after a 1\u20133 home defeat against [[Sevilla FC]] which saw them drop into the 18th position,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=394070&type=story&cc=null|title=Athletico Bilbao appoint Esnal as new coach|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=29 November 2006|access-date=24 March 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024131147/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=394070&type=story&cc=null|archive-date=24 October 2012|df=}}</ref> and eventually again [[2006\u201307 La Liga|barely avoiding relegation]].\n\nIn June 2009, Sarriugarte signed at [[CD Varea]] (soon to be named [[UD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]]), [[2008\u201309 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|freshly promoted]] to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], but stepped down before [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the campaign]] began.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elcorreo.com/alava/20090621/deportes/la-rioja/varea-descarta-felix-sarriugarte-20090621.html|title=El Varea descarta a F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte como t\u00e9cnico|trans-title=Varea release F\u00e9lix Sarriugarte as coach|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|language=es|date=21 June 2009|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> On 16 July 2012, after having led [[Sestao River Club]] to [[2011\u201312 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|safety in that level]], he joined another team in the same tier, Oviedo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2012/07/16/futbol/mas_futbol/1342451197.html|title=Sarriugarte ser\u00e1 el nuevo entrenador del Oviedo|trans-title=Sarriugarte to be new Oviedo coach|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=F.|last=Fern\u00e1ndez|language=es|date=16 July 2012|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Charlotte Independence]] announced on 17 January 2019 that Sarriugarte had joined the technical staff of the club as an assistant manager, under [[Jim McGuinness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charlotteindependence.com/news_article/show/986034|title=McGuinness appoints former La Liga manager to assistant coach|publisher=Charlotte Independence|first=James|last=Thomas|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|746}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|746}}\n*{{Athletic Bilbao profile|id=8/sarriugarte}}\n\n{{Charlotte Independence squad}}\n{{Bilbao Athletic managers}}\n{{Athletic Bilbao managers}}\n{{Real Oviedo managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarriugarte, Felix}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Durango, Biscay]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Basque footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Bilbao Athletic footballers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo players]]\n[[Category:UD Las Palmas players]]\n[[Category:Barakaldo CF footballers]]\n[[Category:UDA Gramenet footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao B managers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao managers]]\n[[Category:Sestao River managers]]\n[[Category:Real Oviedo managers]]\n[[Category:Athletic Bilbao non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Lebenglese", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Sarriugarte"}
